# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fire-resistance-rating
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] A **building code** (also **building control** or **building regulations**) is a set of rules that specify the standards for construction objects such as buildings and non-building structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Buildings must conform to the code to obtain planning permission, usually from a local council.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The building code becomes law of a particular jurisdiction when formally enacted by the appropriate governmental or private authority.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Codes regulate the design and construction of structures where adopted into law.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Examples of building codes began in ancient times.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In the USA the main codes are the International Building Code or International Residential Code [IBC/IRC], electrical codes and plumbing, mechanical codes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Fifty states and the District of Columbia have adopted the I-Codes at the state or jurisdictional level.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In Canada, national model codes are published by the National Research Council of Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In the United Kingdom, compliance with Building Regulations is monitored by building control bodies, either Approved Inspectors or Local Authority Building Control departments.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Building Control regularisation charges apply in case work is undertaken which should have had been inspected at the time of the work if this was not done.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The practice of developing, approving, and enforcing building codes varies considerably among nations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In some countries building codes are developed by the government agencies or quasi-governmental standards organizations and then enforced across the country by the central government.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Such codes are known as the **national building codes** (in a sense they enjoy a mandatory nationwide application).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In other countries, where the power of regulating construction and fire safety is vested in local authorities, a system of model building codes is used.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Model building codes have no legal status unless adopted or adapted by an authority having jurisdiction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The developers of model codes urge public authorities to reference model codes in their laws, ordinances, regulations, and administrative orders.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] When referenced in any of these legal instruments, a particular model code becomes law.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] This practice is known as 'adoption by reference'.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] When an adopting authority decides to delete, add, or revise any portions of the model code adopted, it is usually required by the model code developer to follow a formal adoption procedure in which those modifications can be documented for legal purposes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] There are instances when some local jurisdictions choose to develop their own building codes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] At some point in time all major cities in the United States had their own building codes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] However, due to ever increasing complexity and cost of developing building regulations, virtually all municipalities in the country have chosen to adopt model codes instead.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] For example, in 2008 New York City abandoned its proprietary *1968 New York City Building Code* in favor of a customized version of the International Building Code.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The City of Chicago remains the only municipality in America that continues to use a building code the city developed on its own as part of the *Municipal Code of Chicago*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In Europe, the Eurocode: Basis of structural design, is a pan-European building code that has superseded the older national building codes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Each country now has National Annexes to localize the contents of the Eurocodes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Similarly, in India, each municipality and urban development authority has its own building code, which is mandatory for all construction within their jurisdiction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] All these local building codes are variants of a National Building Code, which serves as model code proving guidelines for regulating building construction activity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The purpose of building codes is to provide minimum standards for safety, health, and general welfare including structural integrity, mechanical integrity (including sanitation, water supply, light, and ventilation), means of egress, fire prevention and control, and energy conservation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Building codes are generally separate from zoning ordinances, but exterior restrictions (such as setbacks) may fall into either category.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Designers use building code standards out of substantial reference books during design.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Building departments review plans submitted to them before construction, issue permits [or not] and inspectors verify compliance to these standards at the site during construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] There are often additional codes or sections of the same building code that have more specific requirements that apply to dwellings or places of business and special construction objects such as canopies, signs, pedestrian walkways, parking lots, and radio and television antennas.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Building codes have been criticized for contributing to housing crisis and increasing the cost of new housing to some extent, including through conflicting code between different administrators.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Proposed improvements include regular review and cost-benefit analysis of building codes, promotion of low-cost construction materials and building codes suitable to mass production, reducing bureaucracy, and promoting transparency.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The earliest known written building code is included in the Code of Hammurabi, which dates from circa 1772 BC.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The book of Deuteronomy in the Hebrew Bible stipulated that parapets must be constructed on all houses to prevent people from falling off.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In the Chinese book of rites it mentions that ancestral temples and houses should be a certain standard length in ancient China they measured land in the chu or well field system so it was important to be precise though most of the actual lengths are lost or obscure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In ancient Japan a certain official destroyed a courtiers house because the size was above his rank.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In Paris, under the reconstruction of much of the city under the Second Empire (1852–70), great blocks of apartments were erected and the height of buildings was limited by law to five or six stories at most.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] After the Great Fire of London in 1666, which had been able to spread so rapidly through the densely built timber housing of the city, the Rebuilding of London Act 1666 was passed in the same year as the first significant building regulation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Drawn up by Sir Matthew Hale, the act regulated the rebuilding of the city, required housing to have some fire resistance capacity and authorised the City of London Corporation to reopen and widen roads.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The Laws of the Indies were passed in the 1680s by the Spanish Crown to regulate the urban planning for colonies throughout Spain's worldwide imperial possessions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The first systematic national building standard was established with the Metropolitan Buildings Act 1844.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The Metropolitan Buildings Office was formed to regulate the construction and use of buildings throughout London.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Surveyors were empowered to enforce building regulations, which sought to improve the standard of houses and business premises, and to regulate activities that might threaten public health.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In 1855 the assets, powers and responsibilities of the office passed to the Metropolitan Board of Works.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The City of Baltimore passed its first building code in 1891.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The Great Baltimore Fire occurred in February 1904.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Subsequent changes were made that matched other cities.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] In 1904, a Handbook of the Baltimore City Building Laws was published.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] It served as the building code for four years.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Very soon, a formal building code was drafted and eventually adopted in 1908.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The structural failure of the tank that caused the Great Molasses Flood of 1919 prompted the Boston Building Department to require engineering and architectural calculations be filed and signed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] U.S. cities and states soon began requiring sign-off by registered professional engineers for the plans of major buildings.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] More recently, the 2015 Berkeley balcony collapse has prompted updates to California's balcony building codes, set for 2025, which include stricter material requirements, enhanced load-bearing standards, and mandatory inspections which known as SB326 and SB721.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] These laws mandate regular inspections every six years for multifamily buildings.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Property owners and HOAs are required to address any structural or waterproofing issues identified during inspections to ensure compliance and safety.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Failure to comply can result in fines, increased liability, and legal consequences.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] The current energy codes of the United States are adopted at the state and municipal levels and are based on the International Energy Conservation Code (IECC).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Previously, they were based on the Model Energy Code (MEC).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building-code] Australia uses the National Construction Code.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] A **building** or **edifice** is an enclosed structure with a roof, walls and often windows, usually standing permanently in one place, such as a house or factory.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings come in a variety of sizes, shapes, and functions, and have been adapted throughout history for numerous factors, from building materials available, to weather conditions, land prices, ground conditions, specific uses, prestige, and aesthetic reasons.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] To better understand the concept, see *Nonbuilding structure* for contrast.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings serve several societal needs – occupancy, primarily as shelter from weather, security, living space, privacy, to store belongings, and to comfortably live and work.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] A building as a shelter represents a physical separation of the human habitat (a place of comfort and safety) from the *outside* (a place that may be harsh and harmful at times).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings have been objects or canvasses of much artistic expression.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] In recent years, interest in sustainable planning and building practices has become an intentional part of the design process of many new buildings and other structures, usually green buildings.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] A building is 'a structure that has a roof and walls and stands more or less permanently in one place'; "there was a three-storey building on the corner"; "it was an imposing edifice".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] In the broadest interpretation a fence or wall is a building.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] However, the word *structure* is used more broadly than *building*, to include natural and human-made formations and ones that do not have walls; *structure* is more often used for a fence.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] There is clear evidence of homebuilding from around 18,000 BC.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings became common during the Neolithic period.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Single-family residential buildings are most often called *houses* or *homes*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Multi-family residential buildings containing more than one dwelling unit are called *duplexes* or *apartment buildings*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] *Condominiums* are apartments that occupants own rather than rent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Houses may be built in pairs (semi-detached) or in terraces, where all but two of the houses have others on either side.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Apartments may be built around courtyards or as rectangular blocks surrounded by plots of ground.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Houses built as single dwellings may later be divided into apartments or bedsitters, or converted to other uses (e.g., offices or shops).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Hotels, especially of the extended-stay variety (apartels), can be classed as residential.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Building types may range from huts to multimillion-dollar high-rise apartment blocks able to house thousands of people.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Increasing settlement density in buildings (and smaller distances between buildings) is usually a response to high ground prices resulting from the desire of many people to live close to their places of employment or similar attractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] For residents in need of special care or those society considers dangerous enough to deprive of liberty, there are institutions (nursing homes, orphanages, psychiatric hospitals, and prisons) and group housing (barracks and dormitories).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Historically, many people lived in communal buildings called longhouses, smaller dwellings called pit-houses, and houses combined with barns, sometimes called housebarns.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Common building materials include brick, concrete, stone, and combinations thereof.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings are defined to be substantial, permanent structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Such forms as yurts and motorhomes are therefore considered *dwellings* but not *buildings*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] A commercial building is one in which at least one business is based and people do not live.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Examples include stores, restaurant, and hotels.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Industrial buildings are those in which heavy industry is done, such as manufacturing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] These edifices include warehouses and factories.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Agricultural buildings are the outbuildings, such as barns located on farms.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Some buildings incorporate several or multiple different uses, most commonly commercial and residential.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Sometimes a group of interrelated (and possibly inter-connected) builds are referred to as a complex – for example, a housing complex, educational complex, hospital complex, etc.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] The practice of designing, constructing, and operating buildings is generally a collective effort of different groups of professionals and trades.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings are typically subject to planning and building regulations depending on their jurisdiction, including zoning ordinances, building codes, and other regulations such as fire codes, life safety codes, and related standards.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Vehicles—such as trailers, caravans, ships, and passenger aircraft—are treated as "buildings" for life safety purposes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings represent a large part of energy, electricity, water, and materials consumption.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] As of 2020, they account for 37% of global energy use and energy-related CO2 emissions, which the United Nations estimates contributed to 33% of overall worldwide emissions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Including the manufacturing of building materials, the global CO2 emissions were 39%.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] If new technologies in construction are not adopted during this time of rapid growth, emissions could double by 2050, according to the United Nations Environment Program.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Glass buildings, especially all-glass skyscrapers, contribute significantly to climate change due to their energy inefficiency.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] While these structures are visually appealing and allow abundant natural light, they also trap heat, necessitating increased use of air conditioning systems, which contributes to higher carbon emissions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Experts advocate for design modifications and potential restrictions on all-glass edifices to mitigate their detrimental environmental impact.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings account for a large amount of land.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] According to the National Resources Inventory, approximately 107 million acres (430,000 km2) of land in the United States are developed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] The International Energy Agency released a publication that estimated that existing buildings are responsible for more than 40% of the world's total primary energy consumption and for 24% of global carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Any building requires a certain general amount of internal infrastructure to function, which includes such elements like heating / cooling, power and telecommunications, water and wastewater etc.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Especially in commercial buildings (such as offices or factories), these can be extremely intricate systems taking up large amounts of space (sometimes located in separate areas or double floors / false ceilings) and constitute a big part of the regular maintenance required.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings may be damaged during construction or during maintenance.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] They may be damaged by accidents involving storms, explosions, subsidence caused by mining, water withdrawal or poor foundations and landslides.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] Buildings may suffer fire damage and flooding.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/building] They may become dilapidated through lack of proper maintenance, or alteration work improperly carried out.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples have continuously inhabited what is now Canada for thousands of years.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Beginning in the 16th century, British and French expeditions explored and later settled along the Atlantic coast.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] As a consequence of various armed conflicts, France ceded nearly all of its colonies in North America in 1763.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1867, with the union of three British North American colonies through Confederation, Canada was formed as a federal dominion of four provinces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This began an accretion of provinces and territories resulting in the displacement of Indigenous populations, and a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This increased sovereignty was highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and culminated in the *Canada Act 1982*, which severed the vestiges of legal dependence on the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy in the Westminster tradition.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country's head of government is the prime minister, who holds office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the elected House of Commons and is appointed by the governor general, representing the monarch of Canada, the ceremonial head of state.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country is a Commonwealth realm and is officially bilingual (English and French) in the federal jurisdiction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It is very highly ranked in international measurements of government transparency, quality of life, economic competitiveness, innovation, education and human rights.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It is one of the world's most ethnically diverse and multicultural nations, the product of large-scale immigration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's long and complex relationship with the United States has had a significant impact on its history, economy, and culture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] A developed country, Canada's advanced economy has a high nominal per capita GDP globally and ranks among the largest in the world by nominal GDP, relying chiefly upon its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade networks.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power; its support for multilateralism and internationalism has been closely related to its foreign policies of peacekeeping and aid for developing countries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participation in multiple international organizations and forums.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] While a variety of theories have been postulated for the etymological origins of *Canada*, the name is now accepted as coming from the St.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Lawrence Iroquoian word *kanata*, meaning 'village' or 'settlement'.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1535, Indigenous inhabitants of the present-day Quebec City region used the word to direct French explorer Jacques Cartier to the village of Stadacona.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Cartier later used the word *Canada* to refer not only to that particular village but to the entire area subject to Donnacona (the chief at Stadacona); by 1545, European books and maps had begun referring to this small region along the Saint Lawrence River as *Canada*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] From the 16th to the early 18th century, *Canada* referred to the part of New France that lay along the Saint Lawrence River.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Following the British conquest of New France, this area was known as the British Province of Quebec from 1763 to 1791.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1791, the area became two British colonies called Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] These two colonies were collectively referred to as the Canadas until their union as the Province of Canada in 1841.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Upon Confederation in 1867, *Canada* was adopted as the legal name for the new country at the London Conference and the word *dominion* was conferred as the country's title, reflecting its status as a self-governing nation within the British Empire.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Following the London Declaration of 1949, where it was agreed that India could be a full member of the Commonwealth as a republic, not a dominion, the leaders of the Commonwealth countries agreed that the other members of the Commonwealth should not continue to be referred to as *dominions*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Laurent announced in the Canadian House of Commons that in light of the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and the changes to the Commonwealth, *dominion* was no longer an accurate term to use to refer to Canada and would no longer be used by the federal government.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Similarly, the United Kingdom no longer used the term *dominions* to refer to Canada or other members of the Commonwealth, instead beginning to use the term a *realm of the Commonwealth*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The *Canada Act 1982*, which brought the Constitution of Canada fully under Canadian control, referred only to *Canada*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Later that year, the name of the national holiday was changed from Dominion Day to Canada Day.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The first inhabitants of North America are generally hypothesized to have migrated from Siberia by way of the Bering land bridge and arrived at least 14,000 years ago.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Paleo-Indian archeological sites at Old Crow Flats and Bluefish Caves are two of the oldest sites of human habitation in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The characteristics of Indigenous societies included permanent settlements, agriculture, complex societal hierarchies, and trading networks.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Some of these cultures had collapsed by the time European explorers arrived in the late 15th and early 16th centuries and have only been discovered through archeological investigations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples in present-day Canada include the First Nations, Inuit, and Métis, the last being of mixed descent who originated in the mid-17th century when First Nations people married European settlers and their offspring subsequently developed their own identity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Indigenous population at the time of the first European settlements is estimated to have been between 200,000 and two million, with a figure of 500,000 accepted by Canada's Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] As a consequence of European colonization, the Indigenous population declined by forty to eighty percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Although not without conflict, European Canadians' early interactions with First Nations and Inuit populations were relatively peaceful.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] First Nations and Métis peoples played a critical part in the development of European colonies in Canada, particularly for their role in assisting European coureurs des bois and voyageurs in their explorations of the continent during the North American fur trade.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] These early European interactions with First Nations would change from friendship and peace treaties to the dispossession of Indigenous lands through treaties.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] From the late 18th century, European Canadians forced Indigenous peoples to assimilate into a western Canadian society.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Settler colonialism reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] A period of redress began with the formation of a reconciliation commission by the Government of Canada in 2008.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This included acknowledgment of cultural genocide, settlement agreements, and betterment of racial discrimination issues, such as addressing the plight of missing and murdered Indigenous women.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It is believed that the first documented European to explore the east coast of Canada was Norse explorer Leif Erikson.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In approximately 1000 AD, the Norse built a small short-lived encampment that was occupied sporadically for perhaps 20 years at L'Anse aux Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] No further European exploration occurred until 1497, when seafarer John Cabot explored and claimed Canada's Atlantic coast in the name of Henry VII of England.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1534, French explorer Jacques Cartier explored the Gulf of Saint Lawrence where, on July 24, he planted a 10-metre (33 ft) cross bearing the words, "long live the King of France", and took possession of the territory New France in the name of King Francis I.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The early 16th century saw European mariners with navigational techniques pioneered by the Basque and Portuguese establish seasonal whaling and fishing outposts along the Atlantic coast.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In general, early settlements during the Age of Discovery appear to have been short-lived due to a combination of the harsh climate, problems with navigating trade routes and competing outputs in Scandinavia.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1583, Sir Humphrey Gilbert, by the royal prerogative of Queen Elizabeth I, founded St John's, Newfoundland, as the first North American English seasonal camp.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1600, the French established their first seasonal trading post at Tadoussac along the Saint Lawrence.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] French explorer Samuel de Champlain arrived in 1603 and established the first permanent year-round European settlements at Port Royal (in 1605) and Quebec City (in 1608).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Among the colonists of New France, *Canadiens* extensively settled the Saint Lawrence River valley and Acadians settled the present-day Maritimes, while fur traders and Catholic missionaries explored the Great Lakes, Hudson Bay, and the Mississippi watershed to Louisiana.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Beaver Wars broke out in the mid-17th century over control of the North American fur trade.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The English established additional settlements in Newfoundland in 1610 along with settlements in the Thirteen Colonies to the south.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] A series of four wars erupted in colonial North America between 1689 and 1763; the later wars of the period constituted the North American theatre of the Seven Years' War.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Mainland Nova Scotia came under British rule with the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht and Canada and most of New France came under British rule in 1763 after the Seven Years' War.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 established First Nation treaty rights, created the Province of Quebec out of New France, and annexed Cape Breton Island to Nova Scotia.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] St John's Island (now Prince Edward Island) became a separate colony in 1769.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] To avert conflict in Quebec, the British Parliament passed the Quebec Act 1774, expanding Quebec's territory to the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] More importantly, the Quebec Act afforded Quebec special autonomy and rights of self-administration at a time when the Thirteen Colonies were increasingly agitating against British rule.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It re-established the French language, Catholic faith, and French civil law there, staving off the growth of an independence movement in contrast to the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Proclamation and the Quebec Act in turn angered many residents of the Thirteen Colonies, further fuelling anti-British sentiment in the years prior to the American Revolution.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] After the American War of Independence, the 1783 Treaty of Paris recognized the independence of the United States and set the terms of peace, ceding British North American territories south of the Great Lakes and east of the Mississippi River to the new country.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The American war of independence also caused a large out-migration of Loyalists, the settlers who had fought against American independence.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Many moved to Canada, particularly Atlantic Canada, where their arrival changed the demographic distribution of the existing territories.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] New Brunswick was in turn split from Nova Scotia as part of a reorganization of Loyalist settlements in the Maritimes, which led to the incorporation of Saint John, New Brunswick, as Canada's first city.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] To accommodate the influx of English-speaking Loyalists in Central Canada, the Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the province of Canada into French-speaking Lower Canada (later Quebec) and English-speaking Upper Canada (later Ontario), granting each its own elected legislative assembly.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Canadas were the main front in the War of 1812 between the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Peace came in 1815; no boundaries were changed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Immigration resumed at a higher level, with over 960,000 arrivals from Britain between 1815 and 1850.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] New arrivals included refugees escaping the Great Irish Famine as well as Gaelic-speaking Scots displaced by the Highland Clearances.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Infectious diseases killed between 25 and 33 percent of Europeans who immigrated to Canada before 1891.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The desire for responsible government resulted in the abortive Rebellions of 1837.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Durham Report subsequently recommended responsible government and the assimilation of French Canadians into English culture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Act of Union 1840 merged the Canadas into a united Province of Canada and responsible government was established for all provinces of British North America east of Lake Superior by 1855.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The signing of the Oregon Treaty by Britain and the United States in 1846 ended the Oregon boundary dispute, extending the border westward along the 49th parallel.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This paved the way for British colonies on Vancouver Island (1849) and in British Columbia (1858).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Anglo-Russian Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1825) established the border along the Pacific coast, but, even after the US Alaska Purchase of 1867, disputes continued about the exact demarcation of the Alaska–Yukon and Alaska–British Columbia border.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Following three constitutional conferences, the *British North America Act, 1867* officially proclaimed Canadian Confederation on July 1, 1867, initially with four provinces: Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada assumed control of Rupert's Land and the North-Western Territory to form the Northwest Territories, where the Métis' grievances ignited the Red River Rebellion and the creation of the province of Manitoba in July 1870.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] British Columbia and Vancouver Island (which had been united in 1866) joined the confederation in 1871 on the promise of a transcontinental railway extending to Victoria in the province within 10 years, while Prince Edward Island joined in 1873.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1898, during the Klondike Gold Rush in the Northwest Territories, Parliament created the Yukon Territory.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Alberta and Saskatchewan became provinces in 1905.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Between 1871 and 1896, almost one quarter of the Canadian population emigrated south to the US.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] To settle the West and attract European immigrants, Canada sponsored the construction of three transcontinental railways, enacted the *Dominion Lands Act* and founded the North-West Mounted Police to maintain regional authority.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This period of westward expansion and nation building resulted in the displacement of many Indigenous peoples of the Canadian Prairies to "Indian reserves", clearing the way for ethnic European block settlements.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This caused the collapse of the Plains Bison in western Canada and the introduction of European cattle farms and wheat fields dominating the land.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Indigenous peoples saw widespread famine and disease due to the loss of the bison and their traditional hunting lands.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The federal government did provide emergency relief, on condition of the Indigenous peoples moving to the reserves.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] During this time, Canada introduced the *Indian Act* extending its control over the First Nations to education, government and legal rights.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Because Britain still maintained control of Canada's foreign affairs under the British North America Act, 1867, its declaration of war in 1914 automatically brought Canada into the First World War.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Volunteers sent to the Western Front later became part of the Canadian Corps, which played a substantial role in the Battle of Vimy Ridge and other major engagements of the war.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Conscription Crisis of 1917 erupted when the Unionist Cabinet's proposal to augment the military's dwindling number of active members with conscription was met with vehement objections from French-speaking Quebecers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1919, Canada joined the League of Nations independently of Britain.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Great Depression in Canada during the early 1930s saw an economic downturn, leading to hardship across the country.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In response to the downturn, the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) in Saskatchewan introduced many elements of a welfare state (as pioneered by Tommy Douglas) in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] On the advice of Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, war with Germany was declared effective September 10, 1939, by King George VI, seven days after the United Kingdom.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The delay underscored Canada's independence.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The first Canadian Army units arrived in Britain in December 1939.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In all, over a million Canadians served in the armed forces during the Second World War.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canadian troops played important roles in many key battles of the war, including the failed 1942 Dieppe Raid, the Allied invasion of Italy, the Normandy landings, the Battle of Normandy, and the Battle of the Scheldt in 1944.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada provided asylum for the Dutch monarchy while that country was occupied and is credited by the Netherlands for major contributions to its liberation from Nazi Germany.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Despite another conscription crisis in Quebec in 1944, Canada finished the war with a large army and strong economy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The financial crisis of the Great Depression led the Dominion of Newfoundland to relinquish responsible government in 1934 and become a Crown colony ruled by a British governor.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] After two referendums, Newfoundlanders voted to join Canada in 1949 as a province.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Socially democratic programs were also instituted, such as Medicare, the Canada Pension Plan, and Canada Student Loans; though, provincial governments, particularly Quebec and Alberta, opposed many of these as incursions into their jurisdictions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Finally, another series of constitutional conferences resulted in the *Canada Act 1982*, the patriation of Canada's constitution from the United Kingdom, concurrent with the creation of the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada had established complete sovereignty as an independent country under its own monarchy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1999, Nunavut became Canada's third territory after a series of negotiations with the federal government.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] At the same time, Quebec underwent profound social and economic changes through the Quiet Revolution of the 1960s, giving birth to a secular nationalist movement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The radical Front de libération du Québec (FLQ) ignited the October Crisis with a series of bombings and kidnappings in 1970, and the sovereigntist Parti Québécois was elected in 1976, organizing an unsuccessful referendum on sovereignty-association in 1980.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Attempts to accommodate Quebec nationalism constitutionally through the Meech Lake Accord failed in 1990.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This led to the formation of the Bloc Québécois in Quebec and the invigoration of the Reform Party of Canada in the West.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] A second referendum followed in 1995, in which sovereignty was rejected by a slimmer margin of 50.6 to 49.4 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled unilateral secession by a province would be unconstitutional, and the Clarity Act was passed by Parliament, outlining the terms of a negotiated departure from Confederation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In addition to the issues of Quebec sovereignty, a number of crises shook Canadian society in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada joined the Gulf War in 1990 and was active in several peacekeeping missions in the 1990s, including operations in the Balkans during and after the Yugoslav Wars, and in Somalia, resulting in an incident that has been described as "the darkest era in the history of the Canadian military".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] After the September 11 attacks in the United States, Canada sent troops to Afghanistan in 2001, resulting in the largest amount of Canadian deaths for any single military mission since the Korean War in the early 1950s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 2011, Canadian forces participated in the NATO-led intervention into the Libyan Civil War and also became involved in battling the Islamic State insurgency in Iraq in the mid-2010s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Canada began on January 27, 2020, causing widespread social and economic disruption.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 2021, possible gravesites of Indigenous children were found near former Canadian residential schools, highlighting the cultural genocide against Indigenous peoples.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] A trade war involving the United States began on February 1, 2025, when U.S. president Donald Trump signed orders imposing tariffs on goods entering the United States, alongside rhetoric suggesting the annexation of Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] By total area (including its waters), Canada is the second-largest country.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] By land area alone, Canada ranks fourth, due to having the world's largest area of fresh water lakes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Stretching from the Atlantic Ocean in the east, along the Arctic Ocean to the north, and to the Pacific Ocean in the west, the country encompasses 9,984,670 square kilometres (3,855,100 sq mi) of territory.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is also home to the world's northernmost settlement, Canadian Forces Station Alert, on the northern tip of Ellesmere Island—latitude 82.5°N—which lies 817 kilometres (508 mi) from the North Pole.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In latitude, Canada's most northerly point of land is Cape Columbia in Nunavut at 83°6′41″N, with its southern extreme at Middle Island in Lake Erie at 41°40′53″N.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In longitude, Canada's land extends from Cape Spear, Newfoundland, at 52°37′W, to Mount St.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada can be divided into seven physiographic regions: the Canadian Shield, the Interior Plains, the Great Lakes–St.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Lawrence Lowlands, the Appalachian region, the Western Cordillera, Hudson Bay Lowlands, and the Arctic Archipelago.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Boreal forests prevail throughout the country, ice is prominent in northern Arctic regions and through the Rocky Mountains, and the relatively flat Canadian Prairies in the southwest facilitate productive agriculture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Lawrence River (in the southeast) where the lowlands host much of Canada's economic output.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has over 2,000,000 lakes—563 of which are larger than 100 square kilometres (39 sq mi)—containing much of the world's fresh water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] There are also fresh-water glaciers in the Canadian Rockies, the Coast Mountains, and the Arctic Cordillera.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is geologically active, having many earthquakes and potentially active volcanoes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Average winter and summer high temperatures across Canada vary from region to region.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Winters can be harsh in many parts of the country, particularly in the interior and Prairie provinces, which experience a continental climate, where daily average temperatures are near −15 °C (5 °F), but can drop below −40 °C (−40 °F) with severe wind chills.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In non-coastal regions, snow can cover the ground for almost six months of the year, while in parts of the north snow can persist year-round.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Coastal British Columbia has a temperate climate, with a mild and rainy winter.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] On the east and west coasts, average high temperatures are generally in the low 20s °C (70s °F), while between the coasts, the average summer high temperature ranges from 25 to 30 °C (77 to 86 °F), with temperatures in some interior locations occasionally exceeding 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Much of Northern Canada is covered by ice and permafrost.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The future of the permafrost is uncertain because the Arctic has been warming at three times the global average as a result of climate change in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's annual average temperature over land has risen by 1.7 °C (3.1 °F), with changes ranging from 1.1 to 2.3 °C (2.0 to 4.1 °F) in various regions, since 1948.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The rate of warming has been higher across the North and in the Prairies.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In the southern regions of Canada, air pollution from both Canada and the United States—caused by metal smelting, burning coal to power utilities, and vehicle emissions—has resulted in acid rain, which has severely impacted waterways, forest growth, and agricultural productivity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is one of the largest greenhouse gas emitters globally, with emissions increased by 16.5 percent between 1990 and 2022.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is divided into 15 terrestrial and five marine ecozones.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] These ecozones encompass over 80,000 classified species of Canadian wildlife, with an equal number yet to be formally recognized or discovered.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Although Canada has a low percentage of endemic species compared to other countries, due to human activities, invasive species, and environmental issues in the country, there are currently more than 800 species at risk of being lost.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] About 65 percent of Canada's resident species are considered "Secure".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Over half of Canada's landscape is intact and relatively free of human development.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The boreal forest of Canada is considered to be the largest intact forest on Earth, with approximately 3,000,000 square kilometres (1,200,000 sq mi) undisturbed by roads, cities or industry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Since the end of the last glacial period, Canada has consisted of eight distinct forest regions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Approximately 12.1 percent of the nation's landmass and freshwater are conservation areas, including 11.4 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Approximately 13.8 percent of its territorial waters are conserved, including 8.9 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's first National Park, Banff National Park was established in 1885.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's oldest provincial park, Algonquin Provincial Park was established in 1893.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Established in 2015, Lake Superior National Marine Conservation Area is the world's largest freshwater protected area.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's largest national wildlife region, established in 2018, is the Scott Islands Marine National Wildlife Area.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is described as a "full democracy", with a tradition of liberalism, and an egalitarian, moderate political ideology.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Since the 1960s, an emphasis on social justice has been a distinguishing element of Canada's political culture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Peace, order, and good government, alongside an Implied Bill of Rights, are founding principles of Canadian federalism.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] At the federal level, Canada has been dominated by two relatively centrist parties practising "brokerage politics": the centre-left leaning Liberal Party of Canada and the centre-right leaning Conservative Party of Canada (or its predecessors).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The historically predominant Liberals position themselves at the centre of the political scale.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Far-right and far-left politics have never been a prominent force in Canadian society.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has a parliamentary system within the context of a constitutional monarchy—the monarchy of Canada being the foundation of the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The reigning monarch is also monarch of 14 other sovereign Commonwealth countries and Canada's 10 provinces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The monarch appoints a representative, the governor general, on the advice of the prime minister, to carry out most of their ceremonial royal duties.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The monarchy is the source of sovereignty and authority in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] To ensure the stability of government, the governor general will usually appoint as prime minister the person who is the current leader of the political party that can obtain the confidence of a majority of members in the House.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The leader of the party with the second-most seats usually becomes the leader of the Official Opposition and is part of an adversarial parliamentary system intended to keep the government in check.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Parliament of Canada passes all federal statute laws.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It comprises the monarch, the House of Commons, and the Senate.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] While Canada inherited the British concept of parliamentary supremacy, this was later, with the enactment of the Constitution Act, 1982, all but completely superseded by the American notion of the supremacy of the law.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Each of the 343 members of Parliament in the House of Commons is elected by simple plurality in an electoral district or riding.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The 105 members of the Senate, whose seats are apportioned on a regional basis, serve until age 75.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canadian federalism divides government responsibilities between the federal government and the 10 provinces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Provincial legislatures are unicameral and operate in parliamentary fashion similar to the House of Commons.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's three territories also have legislatures, but these are not sovereign, have fewer constitutional responsibilities than the provinces, and differ structurally from their provincial counterparts.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Constitution of Canada is the supreme law of the country and consists of written text and unwritten conventions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The *Constitution Act, 1867* (known as the British North America Act, 1867 prior to 1982), affirmed governance based on parliamentary precedent and divided powers between the federal and provincial governments.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, granted full autonomy, and the *Constitution Act, 1982*, ended all legislative ties to Britain, as well as adding a constitutional amending formula and the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The *Charter* guarantees basic rights and freedoms that usually cannot be overridden by any government; a notwithstanding clause allows Parliament and the provincial legislatures to override certain sections of the *Charter* for a period of five years.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's judiciary interprets laws and has the power to strike down acts of Parliament that violate the constitution.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Supreme Court of Canada is the highest court, final arbiter, and has been led since 2017 by Richard Wagner, the Chief Justice of Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The governor general appoints the court's nine members on the advice of the prime minister and minister of justice.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The federal Cabinet also appoints justices to superior courts in the provincial and territorial jurisdictions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Common law prevails everywhere except Quebec, where civil law predominates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Criminal law is solely a federal responsibility and is uniform throughout Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Law enforcement, including criminal courts, is officially a provincial responsibility, conducted by provincial and municipal police forces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In most rural and some urban areas, policing responsibilities are contracted to the federal Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canadian Aboriginal law provides certain constitutionally recognized rights to land and traditional practices for Indigenous groups in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Various treaties and case laws were established to mediate relations between Europeans and many Indigenous peoples.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The role of Aboriginal law and the rights they support were reaffirmed by section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] These rights may include provision of services, such as healthcare through the Indian Health Transfer Policy, and exemption from taxation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is a federation composed of 10 federated states, called provinces, and three federal territories.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] These may be grouped into four main regions: Western Canada, Central Canada, Atlantic Canada, and Northern Canada (*Eastern Canada* refers to Central Canada and Atlantic Canada together).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Provinces and territories have responsibility for social programs such as healthcare, education, and social programs, as well as administration of justice (but not criminal law).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Although the provinces collect more revenue than the federal government, equalization payments are made by the federal government to ensure reasonably uniform standards of services and taxation are kept between the richer and poorer provinces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power for its role in global affairs with a tendency to pursue multilateral and international solutions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Globalization has significantly influenced Canadian foreign policies, with the country known for its promotion of peace and security through mediation, and for providing aid to developing countries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada and the United States have a long and complex relationship; historically close allies, they co-operate regularly on military campaigns and humanitarian efforts.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada also maintains historic and traditional ties to the United Kingdom and to France, along with both countries' former colonies through its membership in the Commonwealth of Nations and the *Organisation internationale de la Francophonie*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is noted for having a positive relationship with the Netherlands, owing, in part, to its contribution to the Dutch liberation during the Second World War.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has diplomatic and consular offices in over 270 locations in approximately 180 foreign countries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participating in multiple international organizations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada was a founding member of the United Nations (UN) in 1945 and formed the North American Aerospace Defense Command together with the United States in 1958.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country has membership in the World Trade Organization, the Five Eyes, the G7 and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country was a founding member of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) in 1989 and joined the Organization of American States (OAS) in 1990.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada ratified the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) in 1948, and seven principal UN human rights conventions and covenants since then.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Alongside many domestic obligations, more than 3,000 Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) personnel are deployed in multiple foreign military operations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Canadian unified forces comprise the Royal Canadian Navy, Canadian Army, and Royal Canadian Air Force.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The nation employs a professional, volunteer force of approximately 68,000 active personnel and 27,000 reserve personnel.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In March 2026, Canada achieved the NATO target of spending 2% of its GDP on defence for the 2026 fiscal year.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] This marks a significant increase from previous years—roughly 1.3% to 1.4% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's role in developing *peacekeeping* and its participation in initiatives during the 20th century has played a major role in its positive global image.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Peacekeeping is deeply embedded in Canadian culture and a distinguishing feature that Canadians feel sets their foreign policy apart from the United States.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has long been reluctant to participate in military interventions that are not sanctioned by the United Nations, such as the Vietnam War, the 2003 invasion of Iraq and 2026 Iran war.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Since the 21st century, Canadian direct participation in UN peacekeeping efforts has greatly declined.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The large decrease was a result of Canada directing its participation to UN-sanctioned military operations through the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, rather than directly through the UN.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The change to participation via NATO has resulted in a shift towards more militarized and deadly missions rather than traditional peacekeeping duties.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's mixed-market economy is highly developed, ranking as the world's ninth-largest by nominal GDP as of 2023, at approximately US$2.221 trillion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country is one of the world's largest trading nations, with a highly globalized economy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 2021, Canadian trade in goods and services reached $2.016 trillion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's exports totalled over $637 billion, while its imported goods were worth over $631 billion, of which approximately $391 billion originated from the United States.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 2018, Canada had a trade deficit in goods of $22 billion and a trade deficit in services of $25 billion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Toronto Stock Exchange is the ninth-largest stock exchange in the world by market capitalization, listing over 1,500 companies with a combined market capitalization of over US$2 trillion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Bank of Canada is the central bank of the country.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The minister of finance and minister of innovation, science, and industry use data from Statistics Canada to enable financial planning and develop economic policy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has a strong cooperative banking sector, with the world's highest per-capita membership in credit unions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It ranks low in the Corruption Perceptions Index (14th in 2023) and "is widely regarded as among the least corrupt countries of the world".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It ranks high in the Global Competitiveness Report (19th in 2024).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's economy ranks above most Western nations on the Heritage Foundation's Index of Economic Freedom and experiences a relatively low level of income disparity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country's average household disposable income per capita is "well above" the OECD average.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada ranks among the lowest of the most developed countries for housing affordability and foreign direct investment.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The unemployment rate in 2025 was 6.8 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Since the early 20th century, the growth of Canada's manufacturing, mining, and service sectors has transformed the nation from a largely rural economy to an urbanized, industrial one.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Canadian economy is dominated by the service industry, which employs about three-quarters of the country's workforce.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has an unusually important primary sector, of which the forestry and petroleum industries are the most prominent components.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Many towns in northern Canada, where agriculture is difficult, are sustained by nearby mines or sources of timber.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's economic integration with the United States has increased significantly since the Second World War.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Canada – United States Free Trade Agreement (FTA) of 1988 eliminated tariffs between the two countries, while the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) expanded the free-trade zone to include Mexico in 1994 (later replaced by the Canada–United States–Mexico Agreement).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] As of 2023, Canada is a signatory to 15 free trade agreements with 51 different countries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is one of the few developed nations that are net exporters of energy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Atlantic Canada possess vast offshore deposits of natural gas, and Alberta hosts the fourth-largest oil reserves in the world.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The vast Athabasca oil sands and other oil reserves give Canada 13 percent of global oil reserves, constituting the world's third- or fourth-largest.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada is additionally one of the world's largest suppliers of agricultural products; the Canadian Prairies region is one of the most important global producers of wheat, canola, and other grains.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's main exports are zinc, uranium, gold, nickel, platinoids, aluminum, steel, iron ore, coking coal, lead, copper, molybdenum, cobalt, and cadmium.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has a sizeable manufacturing sector centred in southern Ontario and Quebec, with automobiles and aeronautics representing particularly important industries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country's fishing and tourism industries are also a key contributor to the economy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] In 2020, Canada spent approximately $41.9 billion on domestic research and development, with supplementary estimates for 2022 at $43.2 billion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] As of 2023, the country has produced 15 Nobel laureates in physics, chemistry, and medicine.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The country ranks seventh in the worldwide share of articles published in scientific journals, according to the Nature Index, and is home to the headquarters of a number of global technology firms.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has one of the highest levels of Internet access in the world, with approximately 95 percent of its population aged 15 and above.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada's achievements in science and technology include the creation of the modern alkaline battery, the discovery of insulin, the development of the polio vaccine, and discoveries about the interior structure of the atomic nucleus.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Other major Canadian scientific contributions include the artificial cardiac pacemaker, mapping the visual cortex, the development of the electron microscope, plate tectonics, deep learning, multi-touch technology, and the identification of the first black hole, Cygnus X-1.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has a long history of discovery in genetics, which include stem cells, site-directed mutagenesis, T-cell receptor, and the identification of the genes that cause Fanconi anemia, cystic fibrosis, and early-onset Alzheimer's disease, among numerous other diseases.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] The Canadian Space Agency runs an active space program focused on deep-space, planetary, and aviation research, along with rockets and satellites.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada launched its first satellite, Alouette 1, in 1962.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] It contributes to the International Space Station and is known for its robotic tools, such as multiple Canadarms.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p01] Canada has initiated many long-term projects, including the Radarsat satellite series and the Black Brant rocket series.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The 2021 Canadian census enumerated a total population of 36,991,981, an increase of around 5.2 percent over the 2016 figure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] It is estimated that Canada's population surpassed 40,000,000 in 2023.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The main drivers of population growth are immigration and, to a lesser extent, natural growth.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest per-capita immigration rates in the world, driven mainly by economic policy and family reunification.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] A record 483,390 immigrants were admitted in 2024.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada leads the world in refugee resettlement; it resettled more than 47,600 in 2022.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] New immigrants settle mostly in major urban areas, such as Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's population density, at 4.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (11/sq mi), is among the lowest in the world, with approximately 95 percent of the population residing south of the 55th parallel north.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] About 80 percent of the population lives within 150 kilometres (93 mi) of the border with the contiguous United States.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada is highly urbanized, with over 80 percent of the population living in urban centres.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (over 70 percent) live below the 49th parallel, with 50 percent of Canadians living south of 45°42′ (45.7 degrees) north.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The most densely populated part of the country is the Quebec City–Windsor Corridor in Southern Quebec and Southern Ontario along the Great Lakes and the St.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (81.1 percent) live in family households, 12.1 percent report living alone, and 6.8 percent live with other relatives or unrelated persons.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Fifty-one percent of households are couples with or without children, 8.7 percent are single-parent households, 2.9 percent are multigenerational households, and 29.3 percent are single-person households.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Respondents in the 2021 Canadian census self-reported over 450 "ethnic or cultural origins".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Over 60 percent of Canadians reported a single origin, and 36 percent reported having multiple ethnic origins, thus the overall total is greater than 100 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Of the 36.3 million people enumerated in 2021, approximately 25.4 million reported being "White", representing 69.8 percent of the population.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The Indigenous population representing 5 percent or 1.8 million people, grew by 9.4 percent compared to the non-Indigenous population, which grew by 5.3 percent from 2016 to 2021.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Between 2011 and 2016, the visible minority population rose by 18.4 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In 1961, about 300,000 people, less than two percent of Canada's population, were members of visible minority groups.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The 2021 census indicated that 8.3 million people, or almost one-quarter (23.0 percent) of the population, reported themselves as being or having been a landed immigrant or permanent resident in Canada—above the 1921 census previous record of 22.3 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In 2021, India, China, and the Philippines were the top three countries of origin for immigrants moving to Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] A multitude of languages are used by Canadians, with English and French (the official languages) being the mother tongues of approximately 54 percent and 19 percent of Canadians, respectively.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's official bilingualism policies give citizens the right to receive federal government services in either English or French with official-language minorities guaranteed their own schools in all provinces and territories.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Quebec's 1974 *Official Language Act* established French as the only official language of the province.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Although more than 82 percent of French-speaking Canadians live in Quebec, there are substantial Francophone populations in New Brunswick, Alberta, and Manitoba, with Ontario having the largest French-speaking population outside Quebec.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] New Brunswick, the only officially bilingual province, has an Acadian French minority constituting 33 percent of the population.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] There are also clusters of Acadians in southwestern Nova Scotia, on Cape Breton Island, and in central and western Prince Edward Island.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Other provinces have no official languages as such, but French is used as a language of instruction, in courts, and for other government services, in addition to English.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Manitoba, Ontario, and Quebec allow for both English and French to be spoken in the provincial legislatures and laws are enacted in both languages.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In Ontario, French has some legal status, but is not fully co-official.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] There are 11 Indigenous language groups, composed of more than 65 distinct languages and dialects.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Several Indigenous languages have official status in the Northwest Territories.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Inuktitut is the majority language in Nunavut and is one of three official languages in the territory.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] As of the 2021 census, just over 7.8 million Canadians listed a non-official language as their first language.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The country is also home to many sign languages, some of which are Indigenous.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] American Sign Language (ASL) is used across the country due to the prevalence of ASL in primary and secondary schools.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Quebec Sign Language (LSQ) is used primarily in Quebec.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada is religiously diverse, encompassing a wide range of beliefs and customs.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The Constitution of Canada refers to God; however, Canada has no official church and the government is officially committed to religious pluralism.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Freedom of religion in Canada is a constitutionally protected right.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Rates of religious adherence have steadily decreased since the 1970s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] With Christianity in decline after having once been central and integral to Canadian culture and daily life, Canada has become a post-Christian, secular state.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Although the majority of Canadians consider religion to be unimportant in their daily lives, they still believe in God.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The practice of religion is generally considered a private matter.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] According to the 2021 census, Christianity is the largest religion in Canada, with Roman Catholics representing 29.9 percent of the population having the most adherents.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Christians overall representing 53.3 percent of the population, are followed by people reporting irreligion or having no religion at 34.6 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Other faiths include Islam (4.9 percent), Hinduism (2.3 percent), Sikhism (2.1 percent), Buddhism (1.0 percent), Judaism (0.9 percent), and Indigenous spirituality (0.2 percent).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada has the second-largest national Sikh population, behind India.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Healthcare in Canada is delivered through the provincial and territorial systems of publicly funded health care, informally called Medicare.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] It is guided by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984 and is universal.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Universal access to publicly funded health services "is often considered by Canadians as a fundamental value that ensures national healthcare insurance for everyone wherever they live in the country".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Around 30 percent of Canadians' healthcare is paid for through the private sector.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] This mostly pays for services not covered or partially covered by Medicare, such as prescription drugs, dentistry and optometry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Approximately 65 to 75 percent of Canadians have some form of supplementary health insurance; many receive it through their employers or access secondary social service programs.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Canada is experiencing an increase in healthcare expenditures due to a demographic shift toward an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In 2021, the average age in Canada was 41.9 years.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] A 2016 report by the chief public health officer found that 88 percent of Canadians, one of the highest proportions of the population among G7 countries, indicated that they "had good or very good health".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Eighty percent of Canadian adults self-report having at least one major risk factor for chronic disease: smoking, physical inactivity, unhealthy eating or excessive alcohol use.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest rates of adult obesity among OECD countries, contributing to approximately 2.7 million cases of diabetes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Four chronic diseases—cancer (leading cause of death), cardiovascular diseases, respiratory diseases, and diabetes—account for 65 percent of deaths in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] There are approximately 8 million people aged 15 and older with one or more disabilities in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In 2024, the Canadian Institute for Health Information estimated that healthcare spending reached $372 billion, or 12.4 percent of Canada's GDP for that year.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In 2022, Canada's per-capita spending on health expenditures ranked 12th among health-care systems in the OECD.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The Commonwealth Fund's 2021 report comparing the healthcare systems of the 11 most developed countries ranked Canada second-to-last.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Identified weaknesses were comparatively higher infant mortality rate, the prevalence of chronic conditions, long wait times, poor availability of after-hours care, and a lack of prescription drugs and dental coverage.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] An increasing problem in Canada's health system is a lack of healthcare professionals and hospital capacity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Education in Canada is for the most part provided publicly, funded and overseen by federal, provincial, and local governments.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Education is within provincial jurisdiction and a province's curriculum is overseen by its government.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Education in Canada is generally divided into primary education, followed by secondary and post-secondary education.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Education in both English and French is available in most places across Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada has a large number of universities, almost all of which are publicly funded.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Established in 1663, Université Laval is the oldest post-secondary institution in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The nation's three top ranking universities are the University of Toronto, McGill, and the University of British Columbia.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The largest university is the University of Toronto, which has over 85,000 students.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] According to a 2022 report by the OECD, Canada is one of the most educated countries in the world; the country ranks first worldwide in the percentage of adults having tertiary education, with over 56 percent of Canadian adults having attained at least an undergraduate college or university degree.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada spends an average of 5.3 percent of its GDP on education.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The country invests heavily in tertiary education (more than US$20,000 per student).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] As of 2022, 89 percent of adults aged 25 to 64 have earned the equivalent of a high-school degree, compared to an OECD average of 75 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada is influenced by British, French and Indigenous cultures and traditions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] During the 20th century, Canadians with African, Caribbean, and Asian heritages have added to Canadian identity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's culture draws influences from its broad range of constituent nationalities, and policies that promote a just society are constitutionally protected.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Since the 1960s, Canada has emphasized human rights and inclusiveness for all its people.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian identity shifted from primarily British-based to multicultural between the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The official state policy of multiculturalism is often cited as one of Canada's significant accomplishments and a key distinguishing element of Canadian identity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In Quebec, cultural identity is strong and there is a French Canadian culture that is distinct from English Canadian culture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] As a whole, Canada is in theory a cultural mosaic of regional ethnic subcultures with diverse areas and ethnic enclaves.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's approach to governance emphasizing multiculturalism, which is based on selective immigration, social integration, and suppression of far-right politics, has wide public support.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadians also identify with the country's foreign aid policies, peacekeeping roles, the national park system, and the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Themes of nature, pioneers, trappers, and traders played an important part in the early development of Canadian symbolism.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Modern symbols emphasize the country's geography, northern climate, lifestyles, and the Canadianization of traditional European and Indigenous symbols.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The use of the maple leaf as a symbol dates to the early 18th century in New France.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The maple leaf is depicted on Canada's current and previous flags and on the arms of Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's official tartan, known as the "maple leaf tartan", reflects the colours of the maple leaf through the seasons—green in the spring, gold in the early autumn, red at the first frost, and brown after falling.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The arms of Canada are closely modelled after those of the United Kingdom, with French and distinctive Canadian elements replacing or added to those derived from the British version.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian cuisine items such as Canadian beer, maple syrup, Nanaimo bars, butter tarts, and the Quebec dishes of poutine and tourtière, alongside material items such as tuques, canoes and Hudson's Bay point blanket are considered as uniquely Canadian.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian coins feature many of these symbols: the loon on the $1 coin, the coat of arms on the 50¢ piece, and the beaver on the nickel.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] An image of the monarch appears on $20 bank notes and the obverse of coins.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian literature is often divided into French- and English-language literatures, which are rooted in the literary traditions of France and Britain, respectively.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The earliest Canadian narratives were of travel and exploration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] This developed into three major themes of historical Canadian literature: nature, frontier life, and Canada's position within the world, all of which tie into the garrison mentality.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The evolution of Canadian literature is intricately linked to the country's historical and social contexts, often mirroring the challenges and changes in Canadian society.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] As Canadian literature progressed into the 20th and 21st centuries, it began to address a broader array of subjects and themes, such as women's rights, LGBTQ rights, immigrant experiences, environmental issues, the relationship with Indigenous peoples, and Canadian values and identity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Financial support from governmental bodies, such as the Canada Council for the Arts and various provincial grant programs, facilitates the creation, publication, and promotion of works by Canadian authors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Numerous Canadian authors have received international literary awards including the Nobel Prize in Literature, the Booker Prize, and the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian literary awards and prizes include the Governor General's Literary Awards, the Giller Prize, the Latner Griffin Writers' Trust Poetry Prize, the Burt Award for First Nations, Inuit and Métis Literature and several accolades for literature aimed at children.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Art in Canada is marked by thousands of years of habitation by Indigenous peoples, and, in later times, artists have combined British, French, Indigenous, and American artistic traditions, at times embracing European styles while working to promote nationalism.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The nature of Canadian art reflects these diverse origins, as artists have taken their traditions and adapted these influences to reflect the reality of their lives in Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The Group of Seven is often considered the first uniquely Canadian artistic group and style of painting.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Inuit art since the 1950s has been the traditional gift given to foreign dignitaries by the Canadian government.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Historically, the Catholic Church was the primary patron of art in early Canada, especially Quebec.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The Government of Canada has played a role in the development of art, through the department of Canadian Heritage by giving grants to art galleries, as well as by establishing and funding art schools and colleges across the country, and through the Canada Council for the Arts.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The Canada Council Art Bank also helps artists by buying and publicizing their work.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Great achievements in art in Canada are recognized through various awards and prizes, such as the Molson Prize, the Audain Prize for the Visual Arts, and the Governor General's Visual and Media Arts Awards.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian music reflects a variety of regional scenes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada has developed a vast music infrastructure that includes church halls, chamber halls, conservatories, academies, performing arts centres, record companies, radio stations, music charts, and television music video channels.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Government support programs, such as the Canada Music Fund, assist a wide range of musicians and entrepreneurs who create, produce and market original and diverse Canadian music.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] As a result of its cultural importance, as well as government initiatives and regulations, the Canadian music industry is one of the largest in the world, producing internationally renowned composers, musicians, and ensembles.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Achievements in music are recognized through various awards and prizes, most notably, the Juno Awards presented by the Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The country also hosts numerous music halls of fame with the Canadian Music Hall of Fame honouring musicians at the national level for their lifetime achievements.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] "God Save the King" has been used in Canada since the late 1700s and is the country's de facto royal anthem.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Patriotic music by Canadians dates back over 200 years, with "The Bold Canadian", written in 1812, popular throughout the 19th century.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] "The Maple Leaf Forever", written in 1866, was popular and served as an unofficial national anthem of English Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] "O Canada", originally composed in French in 1880, also served as an unofficial national anthem during the 20th century and was adopted as the country's official anthem in 1980.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's media is highly autonomous, diverse, and very regionalized.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The *Broadcasting Act* declares "the system should serve to safeguard, enrich, and strengthen the cultural, political, social, and economic fabric of Canada".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada has a well-developed media sector, but its cultural output—particularly in English films, television shows, and magazines—is often overshadowed by imports from the United States.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] As a result, the preservation of a distinctly Canadian culture is supported by federal government programs, laws, and institutions such as the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC), the National Film Board of Canada (NFB), and the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian mass media, both print and digital, and in both official languages, is largely dominated by a "handful of corporations".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The largest of these corporations is the country's national public broadcaster, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation, which also plays a significant role in producing domestic cultural content, operating its own radio and TV networks in both English and French.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In addition to the CBC, some provincial governments offer their own public educational TV broadcast services as well, such as TVOntario and Télé-Québec.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Non-news media content in Canada, including film and television, is influenced both by local creators as well as by imports from the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, and France.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In an effort to reduce the amount of foreign-made media, government interventions in television broadcasting can include both regulation of content and public financing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian tax laws limit foreign competition in magazine advertising.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada's official national sports are ice hockey and lacrosse.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Other major professional games include curling, basketball, baseball, soccer, and football.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Great achievements in Canadian sports are recognized by numerous "Halls of Fame" and museums, such as Canada's Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canada shares several major professional sports leagues with the United States.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadian teams in these leagues include seven franchises in the National Hockey League, three Major League Soccer teams, and one team in each of Major League Baseball and the National Basketball Association.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Other popular professional competitions include the Canadian Football League, National Lacrosse League, the Canadian Premier League, and the curling tournaments hosted by Curling Canada.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Canadians identified hockey as their preferred sport for viewing, followed by soccer and then basketball.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] In terms of participation, swimming was the most commonly reported sport by over one-third (35 percent) of Canadians in 2023.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] This was closely followed by cycling (33 percent) and running (27 percent).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] Sports such as golf, volleyball, badminton, bowling, and martial arts are also widely enjoyed at the youth and amateur levels.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/canada-p02] The country co-hosted the 2026 FIFA World Cup alongside Mexico and the United States.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] in Product certification, a **certification listing** is a public record of products that have been tested and approved to meet safety or performance standards, helping installers, inspectors, and regulators ensure products are used correctly.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Typically, subject-related certification listing are required when there are safety constraints associated with product installation and use.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Certification listings are issued by organisations that are usually nationally accredited for doing both testing and product certification work.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Each product in the listing is supported by a **certification document**, which is the official certificate showing that a specific product meets the requirements of a recognized certification program, such as those following ISO/IEC 17065.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Listings and documents are managed by accredited organizations to ensure products are safe, reliable, and consistently compliant.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] A certification listing guides the installation and use of products that have been evaluated and certified for safety and performance.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] In many regulatory contexts, the concept is embedded in formal definitions of “listed,” “certified,” and “labeled” products.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] After a product is installed on-site, a listing enables verification of compliance with relevant regulations, such as building or electrical codes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Certification listings are issued by organizations that are usually nationally accredited for doing both testing and product certification work, in accordance with nationally accredited standards.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Such organizations include Underwriters Laboratories, FM Global, or the Deutsches Institut für Bautechnik (DIBt).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] After testing, the testing laboratory issues a confidential test report to the manufacturer.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] If the product passes the testing required for certification, the items in the test that passed are given a certification listing, which describes the product(s) that were tested, the application, and maximum and minimum tolerances for all components.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] Certification listings are short versions and interpretations of the test results.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/certification-listing] A certification listing indicates that the test has been properly conducted, the tested systems passed, and that a follow-up agreement is in effect between the manufacturer or submitter and the certifier.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] A **firewall** is a fire-resistant barrier used to prevent the spread of fire.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Firewalls are built between or through buildings, structures, or electrical substation transformers, or within an aircraft or vehicle.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Firewalls can be used to subdivide a building into separate fire areas and are constructed in accordance with the locally applicable building codes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Firewalls can be used to separate-high value transformers at an electrical substation in the event of a mineral oil tank rupture and ignition.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] The firewall serves as a fire containment wall between one oil-filled transformer and other neighboring transformers, building structures, and site equipment.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] There are three main classifications of *fire rated walls*: fire walls, fire barriers, and fire partitions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Fire barrier walls are typically continuous from an exterior wall to an exterior wall, or from a floor below to a floor or roof above, or from one fire barrier wall to another fire barrier wall, having a fire resistance rating equal to or greater than the required rating for the application.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Fire barriers are continuous through concealed spaces (e.g., above a ceiling) to the floor deck or roof deck above the barrier.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Fire partitions are not required to extend through concealed spaces if the construction assembly forming the bottom of the concealed space, such as the ceiling, has a fire resistance rating at least equal to or greater than the fire partition.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Portions of structures that are subdivided by fire walls are permitted to be considered separate buildings, in that fire walls have sufficient structural stability to maintain the integrity of the wall in the event of the collapse of the building construction on either side of the wall.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Firewalls are used in varied applications that require specific design and performance specifications.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Knowing the potential conditions that may exist during a fire are critical to selecting and installing an effective firewall.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Performance based design takes into account the potential conditions during a fire.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Understanding thermal limitations of materials is essential to using the correct material for the application.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Laboratory testing is used to simulate fire scenarios and wall loading conditions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] The testing results in an assigned listing number for the fire-rated assembly that defines the expected fire resistance duration and wall structural integrity under the tested conditions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Designers may elect to specify a listed fire wall assembly or design a wall system that would require performance testing to certify the expected protections before use of the designed fire-rated wall system.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] Fire barriers are used around large electrical transformers as firewalls.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/compartmentalization-fire-protection] These barriers are used to isolate one transformer in case of fire or explosions, preventing fire propagation to neighboring transformers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] When aggregate is mixed with dry Portland cement and water, the mixture forms a fluid slurry that can be poured and molded into shape.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The cement reacts with the water through a process called hydration, which hardens it after several hours to form a solid matrix that binds the materials together into a durable stone-like material with various uses.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] This time allows concrete to not only be cast in forms, but also to have a variety of tooled processes performed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The hydration process is exothermic, which means that ambient temperature plays a significant role in how long it takes concrete to set.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Often, additives (such as pozzolans or superplasticizers) are included in the mixture to improve the physical properties of the wet mix, delay or accelerate the curing time, or otherwise modify the finished material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Most structural concrete is poured with reinforcing materials (such as steel rebar) embedded to provide tensile strength, yielding reinforced concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Before the invention of Portland cement in the early 1800s, lime-based cement binders, such as lime putty, were often used.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The overwhelming majority of concretes are produced using Portland cement, but sometimes with other hydraulic cements, such as calcium aluminate cement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Many other non-cementitious types of concrete exist with other methods of binding aggregate together, including asphalt concrete with a bitumen binder, which is frequently used for road surfaces, and polymer concretes that use polymers as a binder.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Whereas concrete is itself a building material, and contains both coarse (large) and fine (small) aggregate particles, mortar contains only fine aggregates and is mainly used as a bonding agent to hold bricks, tiles and other masonry units together.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Grout is another material associated with concrete and cement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It also does not contain coarse aggregates and is usually either pourable or thixotropic, and is used to fill gaps between masonry components or coarse aggregate which has already been put in place.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Some methods of concrete manufacture and repair involve pumping grout into the gaps to make up a solid mass *in situ*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The word concrete comes from the Latin word "*concretus*" (meaning compact or condensed), the perfect passive participle of "*concrescere*", from "*con*-" (together) and "*crescere*" (to grow).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete floors were found in the royal palace of Tiryns, Greece, which dates roughly to 1400 to 1200 BC.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Lime mortars were used in Greece, such as in Crete and Cyprus, in 800 BC.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The Assyrian Jerwan Aqueduct (688 BC) made use of waterproof concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete was used for construction in many ancient structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Small-scale production of concrete-like materials was pioneered by the Nabatean traders who occupied and controlled a series of oases and developed a small empire in the regions of southern Syria and northern Jordan from the 4th century BC.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] They discovered the advantages of hydraulic lime, with some self-cementing properties, by 700 BC.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] They built kilns to supply mortar for the construction of rubble masonry houses, concrete floors, and underground waterproof cisterns.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] They kept the cisterns secret as these enabled the Nabataeans to thrive in the desert.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Some of these structures survive to this day.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The Romans used concrete extensively from 300 BC to AD 476.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] During the Roman Empire, Roman concrete (or *opus caementicium*) was made from quicklime, pozzolana and an aggregate of pumice.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Its widespread use in many Roman structures, a key event in the history of architecture termed the Roman architectural revolution, freed Roman construction from the restrictions of stone and brick materials.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It enabled revolutionary new designs in terms of both structural complexity and dimension.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The Colosseum in Rome was built largely of concrete, and the Pantheon has the world's largest unreinforced concrete dome.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Modern tests show that *opus caementicium* had a similar compressive strength to modern Portland-cement concrete (c.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The long-term durability of Roman concrete structures was found to be due to the presence of pyroclastic (volcanic) rock and ash in the concrete mix.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The crystallization of strätlingite (a complex calcium aluminosilicate hydrate) during the formation of the concrete and its merging with similar calcium–aluminium-silicate–hydrate structures helped give the Roman concrete a greater degree of fracture resistance compared to modern concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] In addition, Roman concrete is significantly more resistant to erosion by seawater than modern concrete; the aforementioned pyroclastic materials react with seawater to form Al-tobermorite crystals over time.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The use of hot mixing in preparation of concrete, leading to the formation of lime clasts in the final product, has been proposed to give the Roman concrete a self-healing ability.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The widespread use of concrete in many Roman structures ensured that many survive to the present day.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The Baths of Caracalla in Rome are just one example.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Many Roman aqueducts and bridges, such as the magnificent Pont du Gard in southern France, have masonry cladding on a concrete core, as does the dome of the Pantheon.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] From the 11th century in England, the increased use of stone in church and castle construction led to an increased demand for mortar.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Quality began to improve in the 12th century through better grinding and sieving.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Medieval lime mortars and concretes were non-hydraulic and were used for binding masonry, "hearting" (binding rubble masonry cores) and foundations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Bartholomaeus Anglicus in his *De proprietatibus rerum* (1240) describes the making of mortar.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] In an English translation from 1397, it reads "lyme ... is a stone brent; by medlynge thereof with sonde and water sement is made".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] From the 14th century, the quality of mortar was again excellent, but only from the 17th century was pozzolana commonly added.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Mayan concrete at the ruins of Uxmal (AD 850–925) is referenced in *Incidents of Travel in the Yucatán* by John L.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] "The roof is flat and had been covered with cement".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Medieval hydraulic mortars were made from the addition of pozzolans such as crushed ceramics, volcanic soils, or metamorphosed soils from specific deposits with known pozzolanic properties, like Trass or noncrystalline opal.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Hydraulic mortar was used in medieval Crete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The use of specific sands containing volcanic ash in 10th-11th century south-Italian mortars may indicate a knowledge of its properties.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The Roman architectural treatise *De architectura* by Vitruvius contained a description of Roman cement and a copy at the scriptorium of Charlemagne produced many of the medieval copies that subsequently survived.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A copy at Saint Gall Abbey was found by Poggio Bracciolini in 1414.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The first printed edition was published in 1486 by Fra Giovanni Sulpitius and versions in Italian, German, French, Spanish, and English were published between 1520 and 1692.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A 16th-century dockyard in Venice used hydraulic lime mortars in foundations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Hydraulic mortar was also used in Ottoman baths in Budapest from the same period.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The *Canal du Midi* was built using concrete in 1670.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Trass from the Rhineland was added to lime in England in the 17th century, including for the mole of English Tangier (1663-1683), which also used Italian pozzolana recommended and supplied by Genoese engineers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] At the port of Toulon, concrete foundations were built using pozzolana or trass, quicklime, sand, pebbles, and slag or cinder.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The 1752 reconstruction of the foundations of Essex bridge by George Semple included a mixture of small stones, sand, and powdered lime.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Perhaps the greatest step forward in the modern use of concrete was Smeaton's Tower, built by British engineer John Smeaton in Devon, England, between 1756 and 1759.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] This third Eddystone Lighthouse pioneered the use of hydraulic lime in concrete, using pebbles and powdered brick as aggregate.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A method for producing Portland cement was developed in England and patented by Joseph Aspdin in 1824.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Aspdin chose the name for its similarity to Portland stone, which was quarried on the Isle of Portland in Dorset, England.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] His son William continued developments into the 1840s, earning him recognition for the development of "modern" Portland cement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Reinforced concrete was invented in 1849 by Joseph Monier. and the first reinforced concrete house was built by François Coignet in 1853.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The first concrete reinforced bridge was designed and built by Joseph Monier in 1875.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Prestressed concrete and post-tensioned concrete were pioneered by Eugène Freyssinet, a French structural and civil engineer.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete components or structures are compressed by tendon cables during, or after, their fabrication in order to strengthen them against tensile forces developing when put in service.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Freyssinet patented the technique on 2 October 1928.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete is an artificial composite material, comprising a matrix of cementitious binder (typically Portland cement paste or asphalt) and a dispersed phase or "filler" of aggregate (typically a rocky material, loose stones, and sand).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The binder "glues" the filler together to form a synthetic conglomerate.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Many types of concrete are available, determined by the formulations of binders and the types of aggregate used to suit the application of the engineered material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] These variables determine strength and density, as well as chemical and thermal resistance of the finished product.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Construction aggregates consist of large chunks of material in a concrete mix, generally a coarse gravel or crushed rocks such as limestone, or granite, along with finer materials such as sand.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Cement paste, most commonly made of Portland cement, is the most prevalent kind of concrete binder.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] For cementitious binders, water is mixed with the dry cement powder and aggregate, which produces a semi-liquid slurry (paste) that can be shaped, typically by pouring it into a form.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The concrete solidifies and hardens through a chemical process called hydration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The water reacts with the cement, which bonds the other components together, creating a robust, stone-like material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Other cementitious materials, such as fly ash and slag cement, are sometimes added—either pre-blended with the cement or directly as a concrete component—and become a part of the binder for the aggregate.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Fly ash and slag can enhance some properties of concrete such as fresh properties and durability.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Alternatively, other materials can also be used as a concrete binder: the most prevalent substitute is asphalt, which is used as the binder in asphalt concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Admixtures are added to modify the cure rate or properties of the material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Mineral admixtures use recycled materials as concrete ingredients.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Conspicuous materials include fly ash, a by-product of coal-fired power plants; ground granulated blast furnace slag, a by-product of steelmaking; and silica fume, a by-product of industrial electric arc furnaces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Structures employing Portland cement concrete usually include steel reinforcement because this type of concrete can be formulated with high compressive strength, but always has lower tensile strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Therefore, it is usually reinforced with materials that are strong in tension, typically steel rebar.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The *mix design* depends on the type of structure being built, how the concrete is mixed and delivered, and how it is placed to form the structure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Portland cement is the most common type of cement in general usage.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It is a basic ingredient of concrete, mortar, and many plasters.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It consists of a mixture of calcium silicates (alite, belite), aluminates and ferrites—compounds, which will react with water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Portland cement and similar materials are made by heating limestone (a source of calcium) with clay or shale (a source of silicon, aluminium and iron) and grinding this product (called *clinker*) with a source of sulfate (most commonly gypsum).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Cement kilns are extremely large, complex, and inherently dusty industrial installations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Of the various ingredients used to produce a given quantity of concrete, the cement is the most energetically expensive.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Even complex and efficient kilns require 3.3 to 3.6 gigajoules of energy to produce a ton of clinker and then grind it into cement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Many kilns can be fueled with difficult-to-dispose-of wastes, the most common being used tires.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The extremely high temperatures and long periods of time at those temperatures allows cement kilns to efficiently and completely burn even difficult-to-use fuels.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The five major compounds of calcium silicates and aluminates comprising Portland cement range from 5 to 50% in weight.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Combining water with a cementitious material forms a cement paste by the process of hydration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The cement paste glues the aggregate together, fills voids within it, and makes it flow more freely.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] As stated by Abrams' law, a lower water-to-cement ratio yields a stronger, more durable concrete, whereas more water gives a freer-flowing concrete with a higher slump.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The hydration of cement involves many concurrent reactions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The process involves polymerization, the interlinking of the silicates and aluminate components as well as their bonding to sand and gravel particles to form a solid mass.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The hydration (curing) of cement is irreversible.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Fine and coarse aggregates make up the bulk of a concrete mixture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Sand, natural gravel, and crushed stone are used mainly for this purpose.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Recycled aggregates (from construction, demolition, and excavation waste) are increasingly used as partial replacements for natural aggregates, while a number of manufactured aggregates, including air-cooled blast furnace slag and bottom ash are also permitted.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The size distribution of the aggregate determines how much binder is required.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Aggregate with a very even size distribution has the biggest gaps whereas adding aggregate with smaller particles tends to fill these gaps.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The binder must fill the gaps between the aggregate as well as paste the surfaces of the aggregate together, and is typically the most expensive component.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Thus, variation in sizes of the aggregate reduces the cost of concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The aggregate is nearly always stronger than the binder, so its use does not negatively affect the strength of the concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Redistribution of aggregates after compaction often creates non-homogeneity due to the influence of vibration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Decorative stones such as quartzite, small river stones or crushed glass are sometimes added to the surface of concrete for a decorative "exposed aggregate" finish, popular among landscape designers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Admixtures are materials in the form of powder or fluids that are added to the concrete to give it certain characteristics not obtainable with plain concrete mixes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Admixtures are defined as additions "made as the concrete mix is being prepared".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The most common admixtures are retarders and accelerators.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] In normal use, admixture dosages are less than 5% by mass of cement and are added to the concrete at the time of batching/mixing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Inorganic materials that have pozzolanic or latent hydraulic properties; these very fine-grained materials are added to the concrete mix to improve the properties of concrete (mineral admixtures), or as a replacement for Portland cement (blended cements).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Products which incorporate limestone, fly ash, blast furnace slag, and other useful materials with pozzolanic properties into the mix, are being tested and used.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] These developments are ever growing in relevance to minimize the impacts caused by cement use, notorious for being one of the largest producers (at about 5 to 10%) of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete production is the process of mixing the various ingredients—water, aggregate, cement, and any additives—to produce concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Once the ingredients are mixed, workers must put the concrete in place before it hardens.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] In modern usage, most concrete production takes place in a large type of industrial facility called a concrete plant, or often a batch plant.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The usual method of placement is casting in formwork, which holds the mix in shape until it has set enough to hold its shape unaided.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete plants come in two main types, ready-mix plants and central mix plants.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A ready-mix plant blends all of the solid ingredients, while a central mix does the same but adds water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A central-mix plant offers more precise control of the concrete quality.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Central mix plants must be close to the work site where the concrete will be used, since hydration begins at the plant.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Modern concrete is usually prepared as a viscous fluid, so that it may be poured into forms.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The forms are containers that define the desired shape.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete formwork can be prepared in several ways, such as slip forming and steel plate construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Alternatively, concrete can be mixed into drier, non-fluid forms and used in factory settings to manufacture precast concrete products.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Interruption in pouring the concrete can cause the initially placed material to begin to set before the next batch is added on top.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] This creates a horizontal plane of weakness called a *cold joint* between the two batches.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Once the mix is where it should be, the curing process must be controlled to ensure that the concrete attains the desired attributes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] During concrete preparation, various technical details may affect the quality and nature of the product.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete mixes are primarily divided into nominal mix, standard mix and design mix.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Nominal mix ratios are given in volume of ${\text{Cement : Sand : Aggregate}}$ .
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Nominal mixes are a simple, fast way of getting a basic idea of the properties of the finished concrete without having to perform testing in advance.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Various governing bodies (such as British Standards) define nominal mix ratios into a number of grades, usually ranging from lower compressive strength to higher compressive strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The grades usually indicate the 28-day cure strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Thorough mixing is essential to produce uniform, high-quality concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Resonant acoustic mixing has also been found effective in producing ultra-high performance cementitious materials, as it produces a dense matrix with low porosity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Workability is the ability of a fresh (plastic) concrete mix to fill the form/mold properly with the desired work (pouring, pumping, spreading, tamping, vibration) and without reducing the concrete's quality.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Workability depends on water content, aggregate (shape and size distribution), cementitious content and age (level of hydration) and can be modified by adding chemical admixtures, like superplasticizer.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Raising the water content or adding chemical admixtures increases concrete workability.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Excessive water leads to increased bleeding or segregation of aggregates (when the cement and aggregates start to separate), with the resulting concrete having reduced quality.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Changes in gradation can also affect workability of the concrete, although a wide range of gradation can be used for various applications.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Any combination of these factors and others may result in a mix which is too harsh, i.e., which does not flow or spread out smoothly, is difficult to get into the formwork, and which is difficult to surface finish.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Workability can be measured by the concrete slump test, a simple measure of the plasticity of a fresh batch of concrete following the ASTM C 143 or EN 12350-2 test standards.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Slump is normally measured by filling an "Abrams cone" with a sample from a fresh batch of concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The cone is placed with the wide end down onto a level, non-absorptive surface.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It is then filled in three layers of equal volume, with each layer being tamped with a steel rod to consolidate the layer.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] When the cone is carefully lifted off, the enclosed material slumps a certain amount, owing to gravity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A relatively dry sample slumps very little, having a slump value of one to two inches (25 to 51 mm) out of one foot (300 mm).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A relatively wet concrete sample may slump as much as eight inches (200 mm).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Workability can also be measured by the flow table test.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Slump can be increased by addition of chemical admixtures such as plasticizer or superplasticizer without changing the water-cement ratio.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Some other admixtures, especially air-entraining admixture, can increase the slump of a mix.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] High-flow concrete, like self-consolidating concrete, is tested by other flow-measuring methods.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] One of these methods includes placing the cone on the narrow end and observing how the mix flows through the cone while it is gradually lifted.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] After mixing, concrete is a fluid and can be pumped to the location where needed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Concrete must be kept moist during curing to achieve optimal strength and durability.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] During curing hydration occurs, allowing calcium-silicate hydrate (CaO-SiO2-H2O, or "C-S-H" in cement chemist notation) to form.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Over 90% of a mix's final strength is typically reached within four weeks, with the remaining 10% achieved over years or even decades.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The conversion of calcium hydroxide in the concrete into calcium carbonate from absorption of CO2 over several decades further strengthens the concrete and makes it more resistant to damage.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] This carbonation reaction, however, lowers the pH of the cement pore solution and can corrode the reinforcement bars.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Hydration and hardening of concrete during the first three days is critical.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Abnormally fast drying and shrinkage due to factors such as evaporation from wind during placement may lead to increased tensile stresses at a time when it has not yet gained sufficient strength, resulting in greater shrinkage cracking.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The early strength of the concrete can be increased if it is kept damp during the curing process.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Minimizing stress before curing minimizes cracking.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] High-early-strength concrete is designed to hydrate faster, often by increased use of cement that increases shrinkage and cracking.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The strength of concrete changes (increases) for up to three years, depending on the cross-section dimension of elements, and conditions to which the structure is exposed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Addition of short-cut polymer fibers can improve (reduce) shrinkage-induced stresses during curing and increase early and ultimate compression strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Properly curing concrete leads to increased strength and lower permeability and avoids cracking where the surface dries out prematurely.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Care must also be taken to avoid freezing or overheating due to the exothermic setting of cement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Improper curing can cause spalling, reduced strength, poor abrasion resistance and cracking.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] During the curing period, concrete is ideally maintained at controlled temperature and humidity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] To ensure full hydration during curing, concrete slabs are often sprayed with "curing compounds" that create a water-retaining film over the concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Typical films are made of wax or related hydrophobic compounds.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] After the concrete is sufficiently cured, the film is allowed to abrade from the concrete through normal use.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Traditional conditions for curing involve spraying or ponding the concrete surface with water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The adjacent picture shows one of many ways to achieve this, ponding—submerging setting concrete in water and wrapping it in plastic to prevent dehydration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Additional common curing methods include wet burlap and plastic sheeting covering the fresh concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] For higher-strength applications, accelerated curing techniques may be applied to the concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] A common technique involves heating the poured concrete with steam, which serves to both keep it damp and raise the temperature so that the hydration process proceeds more quickly and more thoroughly.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The terms *asphalt* (or *asphaltic*) *concrete*, *bituminous asphalt concrete*, and *bituminous mixture* are typically used only in engineering and construction documents, which define concrete as any composite material composed of mineral aggregate adhered with a binder.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The abbreviation, *AC*, is sometimes used for *asphalt concrete* but can also denote *asphalt content, aerated concrete,* or *asphalt cement*, referring to the liquid asphalt portion of the composite material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Geopolymer concrete is concrete made with geopolymer cement consisting of aluminosilicates which react with an acid or alkaline binder.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Notably, this avoids the use of lime, whose production is a major source of CO2 pollution.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Graphene-enhanced concretes are standard designs of concrete mixes, except that during the cement-mixing or production process, a small amount of chemically engineered graphene (typically < 0.5% by weight) is added.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] These enhanced graphene concretes are designed around the concrete application.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Bacteria such as *Bacillus pasteurii*, *Bacillus pseudofirmus*, *Bacillus cohnii*, *Sporosarcina pasteuri*, and *Arthrobacter crystallopoietes* increase the compression strength of concrete through their biomass.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] CT-5. can reduce corrosion of reinforcement in reinforced concrete by up to four times.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] *Sporosarcina pasteurii* reduces water and chloride permeability.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] *B. pasteurii* increases resistance to acid.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] *Bacillus pasteurii* and *B. sphaericuscan* induce calcium carbonate precipitation in the surface of cracks, adding compression strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] However some forms of bacteria can also be concrete-destroying.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It is widely used in foot and highway bridges where high flexural and compressive strength are indicated.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Pervious concrete is a mix of specially graded coarse aggregate, cement, water, and little-to-no fine aggregates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] This concrete is also known as "no-fines" or porous concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Mixing the ingredients in a carefully controlled process creates a paste that coats and bonds the aggregate particles.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The hardened concrete contains interconnected air voids totaling approximately 15 to 25 percent.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Water runs through the voids in the pavement to the soil underneath.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Air entrainment admixtures are often used in freeze-thaw climates to minimize the possibility of frost damage.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Pervious concrete also permits rainwater to filter through roads and parking lots, to recharge aquifers, instead of contributing to runoff and flooding.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Polymer concretes are mixtures of aggregate and any of various polymers and may be reinforced.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The cement is costlier than lime-based cements, but polymer concretes nevertheless have advantages; they have significant tensile strength even without reinforcement, and they are largely impervious to water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Polymer concretes are frequently used for the repair and construction of other applications, such as drains.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Plant fibers and particles can be used in a concrete mix or as a reinforcement.These materials can increase ductility but the lignocellulosic particles hydrolyze during concrete curing as a result of alkaline environment and elevated temperatures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Such process, that is difficult to measure, can affect the properties of the resulting concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Sulfur concrete is a special concrete that uses sulfur as a binder and does not require cement or water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Volcanic concrete substitutes volcanic rock for the limestone that is burned to form clinker.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] It consumes a similar amount of energy, but does not directly emit carbon as a byproduct.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Volcanic rock/ash are used as supplementary cementitious materials in concrete to improve the resistance to sulfate, chloride and alkali silica reaction due to pore refinement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Also, they are generally cost-effective in comparison to other aggregates, good for semi- and light-weight concretes, and good for thermal and acoustic insulation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Pyroclastic materials, such as pumice, scoria, and ashes are formed from cooling magma during explosive volcanic eruptions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] They are used as supplementary cementitious materials or as aggregates for cements and concretes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] They have been extensively used since ancient times to produce materials for building applications.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] For example, pumice and other volcanic glasses were added as a natural pozzolanic material for mortars and plasters during the construction of the Villa San Marco in the Roman period (89 BC – 79 AD), which remain one of the best-preserved otium villae of the Bay of Naples in Italy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Waste light is a form of polymer modified concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The specific polymer admixture allows the replacement of all the traditional aggregates (gravel, sand, stone) by any mixture of solid waste materials in the grain size of 3–10 mm to form a low-compressive-strength (3–20 N/mm2) product for road and building construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] One cubic meter of waste light concrete contains 1.1–1.3 m3 of shredded waste and no other aggregates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Recycled aggregate concretes are standard concrete mixes with the addition or substitution of natural aggregates with recycled aggregates sourced from construction and demolition wastes, disused pre-cast concrete or masonry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] In most cases, recycled aggregate concrete results in higher water absorption levels by capillary action and permeation, which are the prominent determiners of the strength and durability of the resulting concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The increase in water absorption levels is mainly caused by the porous adhered mortar that exists in the recycled aggregates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] Accordingly, recycled concrete aggregates that have been washed to reduce the quantity of mortar adhered to aggregates show lower water absorption levels compared to untreated recycled aggregates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] The quality of the recycled aggregate concrete is determined by several factors, including the size, the number of replacement cycles, and the moisture levels of the recycled aggregates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] When the recycled concrete aggregates are crushed into coarser fractures, the mixed concrete demonstrates better permeability levels, resulting in an overall increase in strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] In contrast, recycled masonry aggregates provide better qualities when crushed into finer fractures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p01] With each generation of recycled concrete, the resulting compressive strength decreases.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete has relatively high compressive strength, but much lower tensile strength.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Therefore, it is usually reinforced with materials that are strong in tension (often steel).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The elasticity of concrete is relatively constant at low stress levels but starts decreasing at higher stress levels as matrix cracking develops.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete has a very low coefficient of thermal expansion and shrinks as it matures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] All concrete structures crack to some extent, due to shrinkage and tension.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete that is subjected to long-duration forces is prone to creep.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Tests can be performed to ensure that the properties of concrete correspond to specifications for the application.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The ingredients affect the strengths of the material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete strength values are usually specified as the lower-bound compressive strength of either a cylindrical or cubic specimen as determined by standard test procedures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The strengths of concrete are dictated by its function.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Very low-strength—14 MPa (2,000 psi) or less—concrete may be used when the concrete must be lightweight.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Lightweight concrete is often achieved by adding air, foams, or lightweight aggregates, with the side effect that the strength is reduced.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] For most routine uses, 20 to 32 MPa (2,900 to 4,600 psi) concrete is often used.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] 40 MPa (5,800 psi) concrete is readily commercially available as a more durable, although more expensive, option.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Higher-strength concrete is often used for larger civil projects.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Strengths above 40 MPa (5,800 psi) are often used for specific building elements.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] For example, the lower-floor columns of high-rise concrete buildings may use concrete of 80 MPa (11,600 psi) or more, to keep the size of the columns small.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Bridges may use long beams of high-strength concrete to lower the number of spans required.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Occasionally, other structural needs may require high-strength concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] If a structure must be very rigid, concrete of very high strength may be specified, even much stronger than is required to bear the service loads.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Strengths as high as 130 MPa (18,900 psi) have been used commercially for these reasons.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The cement produced for making concrete accounts for about 8% of worldwide CO2 emissions per year (compared to, *e.g.*, global aviation at 1.9%).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The two largest sources of CO2 are produced by the cement manufacturing process, arising from (1) the decarbonation reaction of limestone in the cement kiln (T ≈ 950 °C), and (2) from the combustion of fossil fuel to reach the sintering temperature (T ≈ 1450 °C) of cement clinker in the kiln.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The energy required for extracting, crushing, and mixing the raw materials (construction aggregates used in the concrete production, and also limestone and clay feeding the cement kiln) is lower.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The energy requirement for transportation of ready-mix concrete is also lower because it is produced near the construction site from local resources, typically manufactured within 100 kilometers of the job site.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The overall embodied energy of concrete at roughly 1 to 1.5 megajoules per kilogram is therefore lower than for many structural and construction materials.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Once in place, concrete offers great energy efficiency over the lifetime of a building.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete walls leak air far less than those made of wood frames.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Air leakage accounts for a large percentage of energy loss from a home.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The thermal mass properties of concrete increase the efficiency of both residential and commercial buildings.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] By storing and releasing the energy needed for heating or cooling, concrete's thermal mass delivers year-round benefits by reducing temperature swings inside and minimizing heating and cooling costs.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] While insulation reduces energy loss through the building envelope, thermal mass uses walls to store and release energy.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Modern concrete wall systems use both external insulation and thermal mass to create an energy-efficient building.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Insulating concrete forms (ICFs) are hollow blocks or panels made of either insulating foam or rastra that are stacked to form the shape of the walls of a building and then filled with reinforced concrete to create the structure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete buildings are more resistant to fire than those constructed using steel frames.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Since concrete has lower heat conductivity than steel and can thus last longer under the same fire conditions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is sometimes used as a fire protection for steel frames, for the same effect as above.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete as a fire shield, for example Fondu fyre, can also be used in extreme environments like a missile launch pad.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Options for non-combustible construction include floors, ceilings and roofs made of cast-in-place and hollow-core precast concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] For walls, concrete masonry technology and Insulating Concrete Forms (ICFs) are additional options.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] ICFs are hollow blocks or panels made of fireproof insulating foam that are stacked to form the shape of the walls of a building and then filled with reinforced concrete to create the structure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete also provides good resistance against externally applied forces such as high winds, hurricanes, and tornadoes owing to its lateral stiffness, which results in minimal horizontal movement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] However, this stiffness can work against certain types of concrete structures, particularly where a relatively higher flexing structure is required to resist more extreme forces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] As discussed above, concrete is very strong in compression, but weak in tension.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Larger earthquakes can generate very large shear loads on structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] These shear loads subject the structure to both tensile and compressive loads.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete structures without reinforcement, like other unreinforced masonry structures, can fail during severe earthquake shaking.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Unreinforced masonry structures constitute one of the largest earthquake risks globally.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] These risks can be reduced through seismic retrofitting of at-risk buildings, (e.g. school buildings in Istanbul, Turkey).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is one of the most durable building materials.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] It provides superior fire resistance compared with wooden construction and gains strength over time.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Structures made of concrete can have a long service life.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is used more than any other artificial material in the world.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] As of 2006, about 7.5 billion cubic meters of concrete are made each year, more than one cubic meter for every person on Earth.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The use of reinforcement, in the form of iron was introduced in the 1850s by French industrialist François Coignet, and it was not until the 1880s that German civil engineer G.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is a relatively brittle material that is strong under compression but less in tension.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Unreinforced concrete is unsuitable for many structures as it is relatively poor at withstanding stresses induced by vibrations, wind loading, and so on.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Hence, to increase its overall strength, steel rods, wires, mesh or cables can be embedded in concrete before it is set.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This reinforcement, often known as rebar, resists tensile forces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Reinforced concrete (RC) is a versatile composite and one of the most widely used materials in modern construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] It is made up of different constituent materials with very different properties that complement each other.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] In the case of reinforced concrete, the component materials are almost always concrete and steel.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] These two materials form a strong bond together and are able to resist a variety of applied forces, effectively acting as a single structural element.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Reinforced concrete can be precast or cast-in-place (in situ) concrete, and is used in a wide range of applications such as slab, wall, beam, column, foundation, and frame construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Reinforcement is generally placed in areas of the concrete that are likely to be subject to tension, such as the lower portion of beams.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Usually, there is a minimum of 50 mm cover, both above and below the steel reinforcement, to resist spalling and corrosion which can lead to structural instability.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Other types of non-steel reinforcement, such as Fibre-reinforced concretes are used for specialized applications, predominately as a means of controlling cracking.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Precast concrete is concrete which is cast in one place for use elsewhere and is a mobile material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The largest part of precast production is carried out in the works of specialist suppliers, although in some instances, due to economic and geographical factors, scale of product or difficulty of access, the elements are cast on or adjacent to the construction site.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Precasting offers considerable advantages because it is carried out in a controlled environment, protected from the elements, but the downside of this is the contribution to greenhouse gas emission from transportation to the construction site.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Due to cement's exothermic chemical reaction while setting up, large concrete structures such as dams, navigation locks, large mat foundations, and large breakwaters generate excessive heat during hydration and associated expansion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] To mitigate these effects, *post-cooling* is commonly applied during construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] An early example at Hoover Dam used a network of pipes between vertical concrete placements to circulate cooling water during the curing process to avoid damaging overheating.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Similar systems are still used; depending on the volume of the pour, the concrete mix used, and ambient air temperature, the cooling process may last for many months after the concrete is placed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Various methods also are used to pre-cool the concrete mix in mass concrete structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Another approach to mass concrete structures that minimizes cement's thermal by-product is the use of roller-compacted concrete, which uses a dry mix that has a much lower cooling requirement than conventional wet placement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] It is deposited in thick layers as a semi-dry material then roller compacted into a dense, strong mass.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Raw concrete surfaces tend to be porous and have a relatively uninteresting appearance.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Many finishes can be applied to improve the appearance and preserve the surface against staining, water penetration, and freezing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Examples of improved appearance include stamped concrete where the wet concrete has a pattern impressed on the surface, to give a paved, cobbled or brick-like effect, and may be accompanied with coloration.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Another popular effect for flooring and table tops is polished concrete where the concrete is polished optically flat with diamond abrasives and sealed with polymers or other sealants.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Other finishes can be achieved with chiseling, or more conventional techniques such as painting or covering it with other materials.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The proper treatment of the surface of concrete, and therefore its characteristics, is an important stage in the construction and renovation of architectural structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Prestressed concrete is a form of reinforced concrete that builds in compressive stresses during construction to oppose tensile stresses experienced in use.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This can greatly reduce the weight of beams or slabs, by better distributing the stresses in the structure to make optimal use of the reinforcement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] For example, a horizontal beam tends to sag.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Prestressed reinforcement along the bottom of the beam counteracts this.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] In pre-tensioned concrete, the prestressing is achieved by using steel or polymer tendons or bars that are subjected to a tensile force before casting, or for post-tensioned concrete, after casting.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] More than 55,000 miles (89,000 km) of highways in the United States are paved with this material.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Reinforced concrete, prestressed concrete and precast concrete are the most widely used types of concrete functional extensions in modern days.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] For more information see Brutalist architecture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Once mixed, concrete is typically transported to the place where it is intended to become a structural item.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Various methods of transportation and placement are used depending on the distances involved, quantity needed, and other details of application.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Large amounts are often transported by truck, poured free under gravity or through a tremie, or pumped through a pipe.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Smaller amounts may be carried in a skip (a metal container which can be tilted or opened to release the contents, usually transported by crane or hoist), or wheelbarrow, or carried in toggle bags for manual placement underwater.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Extreme weather conditions (extreme heat or cold; windy conditions, and humidity variations) can significantly alter the quality of concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Many precautions are observed in cold weather placement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Low temperatures significantly slow the chemical reactions involved in hydration of cement, thus affecting the strength development.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Preventing freezing is the most important precaution, as formation of ice crystals can cause damage to the crystalline structure of the hydrated cement paste.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] If the surface of the concrete pour is insulated from the outside temperatures, the heat of hydration will prevent freezing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The minimum strength before exposing concrete to extreme cold is 500 psi (3.4 MPa).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] CSA A 23.1 specified a compressive strength of 7.0 MPa to be considered safe for exposure to freezing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete may be placed and cured underwater.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Care must be taken in the placement method to prevent washing out the cement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Underwater placement methods include the tremie, pumping, skip placement, manual placement using toggle bags, and bagwork.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] A tremie is a vertical, or near-vertical, pipe with a hopper at the top used to pour concrete underwater in a way that avoids washout of cement from the mix due to turbulent water contact with the concrete while it is flowing.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This produces a more reliable strength of the product.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The toggle bag method is generally used for placing small quantities and for repairs.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Wet concrete is loaded into a reusable canvas bag and squeezed out at the required place by the diver.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Care must be taken to avoid washout of the cement and fines.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Bagwork concrete will generally reach full strength within 28 days.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Each bag must be pierced by at least one, and preferably up to four pins.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Bagwork is a simple and convenient method of underwater concrete placement which does not require pumps, plant, or formwork, and which can minimise environmental effects from dispersing cement in the water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Prefilled bags are available, which are sealed to prevent premature hydration if stored in suitable dry conditions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Grouted aggregate is an alternative method of forming a concrete mass underwater, where the forms are filled with coarse aggregate and the voids then completely filled from the bottom by displacing the water with pumped grout.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete roads are more fuel efficient to drive on, more reflective and last significantly longer than other paving surfaces, yet have a much smaller market share than other paving solutions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Modern paving methods and design practices have changed the economics of concrete paving, so that a well-designed and placed concrete pavement will be less expensive on initial costs and significantly less expensive over the life cycle.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Another major benefit is that pervious concrete can be used, which eliminates the need to place storm drains near the road and reduces the need for a slightly sloped roadway to help rainwater run off.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] No longer requiring discarding rainwater through use of drains also means that less electricity is needed (more pumping is otherwise needed in the water-distribution system), and no rainwater gets polluted as it no longer mixes with polluted water.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Rather, it is immediately absorbed by the ground.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Cement molded into a forest of tubular structures can be 5.6 times more resistant to cracking/failure than standard concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The approach mimics mammalian cortical bone that features elliptical, hollow osteons suspended in an organic matrix, connected by relatively weak "cement lines".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Cement lines provide a preferred in-plane crack path.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This design fails via a "stepwise toughening mechanism".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Cracks are contained within the tube, reducing spreading, by dissipating energy at each tube/step.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The manufacture and use of concrete produce a wide range of environmental, economic and social impacts.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Grinding of concrete can produce hazardous dust.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Exposure to cement dust can lead to issues such as silicosis, kidney disease, skin irritation and similar effects.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] National Institute for Occupational Safety and Healthrecommends attaching local exhaust ventilation shrouds to electric concrete grinders to control the spread of this dust.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] In addition, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has placed more stringent regulations on companies whose workers regularly come into contact with silica dust.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] An updated silica rule, which OSHA put into effect on 23 September 2017 for construction companies, restricted the amount of breathable crystalline silica workers could legally come into contact with to 50 micrograms per cubic meter of air per 8-hour workday.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] That same rule went into effect 23 June 2018 for general industry, hydraulic fracturing and maritime.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] That deadline was extended to 23 June 2021 for engineering controls in the hydraulic fracturing industry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Companies which fail to meet the tightened safety regulations can face financial charges and extensive penalties.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The presence of some substances in concrete, including useful and unwanted additives, can cause health concerns due to toxicity and radioactivity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Fresh concrete (before curing is complete) is highly alkaline and must be handled with proper protective equipment.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] A major component of concrete is cement, a fine powder used mainly to bind sand and coarser aggregates together in concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Although a variety of cement types exist, the most common is "Portland cement", which is produced by mixing clinker with smaller quantities of other additives such as gypsum and ground limestone.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The production of clinker, the main constituent of cement, is responsible for the bulk of the sector's greenhouse gas emissions, including both energy intensity and process emissions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The cement industry is one of the three primary producers of carbon dioxide, a major greenhouse gas – the other two being energy production and transportation industries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] On average, every tonne of cement produced releases one tonne of CO2 into the atmosphere.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Pioneer cement manufacturers have claimed to reach lower carbon intensities, with 590 kg of CO2eq per tonne of cement produced.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The emissions are due to combustion and calcination processes, which roughly account for 40% and 60% of the greenhouse gases, respectively.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Considering that cement is only a fraction of the constituents of concrete, it is estimated that a tonne of concrete is responsible for emitting about 100–200 kg of CO2.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Every year more than 10 billion tonnes of concrete are used worldwide.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] In the coming years, large quantities of concrete will continue to be used, and the mitigation of CO2 emissions from the sector will be even more critical.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is used to create hard surfaces that contribute to surface runoff, which can cause heavy soil erosion, water pollution, and flooding, but conversely can be used to divert, dam, and control flooding.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete dust released by building demolition and natural disasters can be a major source of dangerous air pollution.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is a contributor to the urban heat island effect, though less so than asphalt.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Reducing the cement clinker content might have positive effects on the environmental life-cycle assessment of concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Some research work on reducing the cement clinker content in concrete has already been carried out.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] However, there exist different research strategies.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Often replacement of some clinker with large amounts of slag or fly ash was investigated based on conventional concrete technology.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This could lead to a waste of scarce raw materials such as slag and fly ash.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The aim of other research activities is the efficient use of cement and reactive materials like slag and fly ash in concrete based on a modified mix design approach.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The embodied carbon of a precast concrete facade can be reduced by 50% when using the presented fiber-reinforced high-performance concrete in place of typical reinforced concrete cladding.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Studies have been conducted about the commercialization of low-carbon concretes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Life cycle assessment (LCA) of low-carbon concrete was investigated according to the ground granulated blast-furnace slag (GGBS) and fly ash (FA) replacement ratios.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Global warming potential (GWP) of GGBS decreased by 1.1 kg CO2 eq/m3, while FA decreased by 17.3 kg CO2 eq/m3 when the mineral admixture replacement ratio was increased by 10%.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This study also compared the compressive strength properties of binary blended low-carbon concrete according to the replacement ratios, and the applicable range of mixing proportions was derived.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] High-performance building materials will be particularly important for enhancing resilience, including for flood defenses and critical-infrastructure protection.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Risks to infrastructure and cities posed by extreme weather events are especially serious for those places exposed to flood and hurricane damage, but also where residents need protection from extreme summer temperatures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Traditional concrete can come under strain when exposed to humidity and higher concentrations of atmospheric CO2.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] While concrete is likely to remain important in applications where the environment is challenging, novel, smarter and more adaptable materials are also needed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete degradation may have many different causes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete is mostly damaged by the corrosion of reinforcement bars, the carbonatation of hardened cement paste or chloride attack under wet conditions.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Concrete recycling is the use of rubble from demolished concrete structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Recycling is cheaper and more ecological than trucking rubble to a landfill.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Crushed rubble can be used for road gravel, revetments, retaining walls, landscaping gravel, or raw material for new concrete.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Large pieces can be used as bricks or slabs, or incorporated with new concrete into structures, a material called urbanite.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] There have been concerns about the recycling of painted concrete due to possible lead content.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Studies have indicated that recycled concrete exhibits lower strength and durability compared to concrete produced using natural aggregates.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This deficiency can be addressed by incorporating supplementary materials such as fly ash into the mixture.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Recygenie has built a 220-unit housing complex out of 100% recycled concrete, strengthening the concrete by adding recycled sand, steel slag, and other byproducts.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The world record for the largest concrete pour in a single project is the Three Gorges Dam in Hubei Province, China by the Three Gorges Corporation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The amount of concrete used in the construction of the dam is estimated at 16 million cubic meters over 17 years.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The previous record was 12.3 million cubic meters held by the Itaipu hydropower station in Brazil.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The world record for concrete pumping was set on 7 August 2009 during the construction of the Parbati Hydroelectric Project, near the village of Suind, Himachal Pradesh, India, when the concrete mix was pumped through a vertical height of 715 m (2,346 ft).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The Polavaram dam works in Andhra Pradesh on 6 January 2019 entered the Guinness World Records by pouring 32,100 cubic metres of concrete in 24 hours.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The world record for the largest continuously poured concrete raft was achieved in August 2007 in Abu Dhabi by contracting firm Al Habtoor-CCC Joint Venture and the concrete supplier is Unibeton Ready Mix.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The pour (a part of the foundation for the Abu Dhabi's Landmark Tower) was 16,000 cubic meters of concrete poured within a two-day period.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The world record for largest continuously poured concrete floor was completed on 8 November 1997, in Louisville, Kentucky by design-build firm EXXCEL Project Management.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The monolithic placement consisted of 225,000 square feet (20,900 m2) of concrete placed in 30 hours, finished to a flatness tolerance of FF 54.60 and a levelness tolerance of FL 43.83.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] This surpassed the previous record by 50% in total volume and 7.5% in total area.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The record for the largest continuously placed underwater concrete pour was completed 18 October 2010, in New Orleans, Louisiana by contractor C.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Mahan Construction Company, LLC of Grove City, Ohio.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] The placement consisted of 10,251 cubic yards of concrete placed in 58.5 hours using two concrete pumps and two dedicated concrete batch plants.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Upon curing, this placement allows the 50,180-square-foot (4,662 m2) cofferdam to be dewatered approximately 26 feet (7.9 m) below sea level to allow the construction of the Inner Harbor Navigation Canal Sill & Monolith Project to be completed in the dry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/concrete-p02] Its appearance is also imitated in other media: for example Congolese artist Sardoine Mia creates canvases that look like concrete surfaces.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The construction industry contributes significantly to many countries' gross domestic products (GDP).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Global expenditure on construction activities was about $4 trillion in 2012.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In 2022, expenditure on the construction industry exceeded $11 trillion a year, equivalent to about 13 percent of global GDP.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] This spending was forecasted to rise to around $14.8 trillion in 2030.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The construction industry promotes economic development and brings many non-monetary benefits to many countries, but it is one of the most hazardous industries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] For example, about 20% (1,061) of US industry fatalities in 2019 happened in construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] "Construction" stems from the Latin word *constructio* (which comes from *com-* "together" and *struere* "to pile up") as well as Old French *construction*.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] "To construct" is a verb: the act of building.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The noun is "construction": how something is built or the nature of its structure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The first huts and shelters were constructed by hand or with simple tools.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] As cities grew during the Bronze Age, a class of professional craftsmen, like bricklayers and carpenters, appeared.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Occasionally, slaves were used for construction work.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the Middle Ages, the artisan craftsmen were organized into craft guilds.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the 19th century, steam-powered machinery appeared, and later, diesel- and electric-powered vehicles such as cranes, excavators and bulldozers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Fast-track construction has been increasingly popular in the 21st century.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some estimates suggest that 40% of construction projects are now fast-track construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The industry can also be classified into sectors or markets.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] For example, *Engineering News-Record* (*ENR*), a US-based construction trade magazine, has compiled and reported data about the size of design and construction contractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In 2014, it split the data into nine market segments: transportation, petroleum, buildings, power, industrial, water, manufacturing, sewage/waste, telecom, hazardous waste, and a tenth category for other projects.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] *ENR* used data on transportation, sewage, hazardous waste and water to rank firms as heavy contractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The Standard Industrial Classification and the newer North American Industry Classification System classify companies that perform or engage in construction into three subsectors: building construction, heavy and civil engineering construction, and specialty trade contractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] There are also categories for professional services firms (e.g., engineering, architecture, surveying, project management).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Building construction is the process of adding structures to areas of land, also known as real property sites.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Typically, a project is instigated by or with the owner of the property (who may be an individual or an organisation); occasionally, land may be compulsorily purchased from the owner for public use.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Residential construction may be undertaken by individual land-owners (self-built), by specialist housebuilders, by property developers, by general contractors, or by providers of public or social housing (e.g.: local authorities, housing associations).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Where local zoning or planning policies allow, mixed-use developments may comprise both residential and non-residential construction (e.g.: retail, leisure, offices, public buildings, etc.).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Residential construction practices, technologies, and resources must conform to local building authority's regulations and codes of practice.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Materials readily available in the area generally dictate the construction materials used (e.g.: brick versus stone versus timber).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Costs of construction on a per square meter (or per square foot) basis for houses can vary dramatically based on site conditions, access routes, local regulations, economies of scale (custom-designed homes are often more expensive to build) and the availability of skilled tradespeople.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Most construction in these sectors is undertaken by general contractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Civil engineering covers the design, construction, and maintenance of the physical and naturally built environment, including public works such as roads, bridges, canals, dams, tunnels, airports, water and sewerage systems, pipelines, and railways.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some general contractors have expertise in civil engineering; civil engineering contractors are firms dedicated to work in this sector, and may specialise in particular types of infrastructure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Industrial construction includes offshore construction (mainly of energy installations: oil and gas platforms, wind power), mining and quarrying, refineries, food processing plants, breweries and distilleries, power stations, steel mills, warehouses and factories.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some construction projects are small renovations or repair jobs, like repainting or fixing leaks, where the owner may act as designer, paymaster and labourer for the entire project.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] However, more complex or ambitious projects usually require additional multi-disciplinary expertise and manpower, so the owner may commission one or more specialist businesses to undertake detailed planning, design, construction and handover of the work.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Contracts are agreed for the delivery of services by all businesses, alongside other detailed plans aimed at ensuring legal, timely, on-budget and safe delivery of the specified works.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Design, finance, and legal aspects overlap and interrelate.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The design must be not only structurally sound and appropriate for the use and location, but must also be financially possible to build, and legal to use.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The financial structure must be adequate to build the design provided and must pay amounts that are legally owed.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Legal structures integrate design with other activities and enforce financial and other construction processes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] These processes also affect procurement strategies.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some forms of procurement emphasize collaborative relationships (partnering, alliancing) between the client, the contractor, and other stakeholders within a construction project, seeking to ameliorate often highly competitive and adversarial industry practices.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] DfMA (design for manufacture and assembly) and so-called modern methods of construction approaches also emphasize early collaboration with manufacturers and suppliers regarding products and components.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Construction or refurbishment work in a "live" environment (where residents or businesses remain living in or operating on the site) requires particular care, planning and communication.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] When applicable, a proposed construction project must comply with local land-use planning policies including zoning and building code requirements.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Data may be gathered through site analysis, site surveys and geotechnical investigations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Construction normally cannot start until planning permission has been granted, and may require preparatory work to ensure relevant infrastructure has been upgraded before building work can commence.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Preparatory works will also include surveys of existing utility lines to avoid damage-causing outages and other hazardous situations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some legal requirements come from *malum in se* considerations, or the desire to prevent indisputably bad phenomena, e.g. explosions or bridge collapses.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Other legal requirements come from *malum prohibitum* considerations, or factors that are a matter of custom or expectation, such as isolating businesses from a business district or residences from a residential district.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] During the construction of a building, a municipal building inspector usually inspects the ongoing work periodically to ensure that construction adheres to the approved plans and the local building code.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Once construction is complete, any later changes made to a building or other asset that affect safety, including its use, expansion, structural integrity, and fire protection, usually require municipality approval.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Depending on the type of project, mortgage bankers, accountants, and cost engineers may participate in creating an overall plan for the financial management of a construction project.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The presence of the mortgage banker is highly likely, even in relatively small projects since the owner's equity in the property is the most obvious source of funding for a building project.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Accountants act to study the expected monetary flow over the life of the project and to monitor the payouts throughout the process.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Professionals including cost engineers, estimators and quantity surveyors apply expertise to relate the work and materials involved to a proper valuation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Financial planning ensures adequate safeguards and contingency plans are in place before the project is started, and ensures that the plan is properly executed over the life of the project.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Construction projects can suffer from preventable financial problems.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Underbids happen when builders ask for too little money to complete the project.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Cash flow problems exist when the present amount of funding cannot cover the current costs for labour and materials; such problems may arise even when the overall budget is adequate, presenting a temporary issue.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Cost overruns with government projects have occurred when the contractor identified change orders or project changes that increased costs, which are not subject to competition from other firms as they have already been eliminated from consideration after the initial bid.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Fraud is also an issue of growing significance within construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Large projects can involve highly complex financial plans and often start with a conceptual cost estimate performed by a building estimator.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] As portions of a project are completed, they may be sold, supplanting one lender or owner for another, while the logistical requirements of having the right trades and materials available for each stage of the building construction project carry forward.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Public–private partnerships (PPPs) or private finance initiatives (PFIs) may also be used to help deliver major projects.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] According to McKinsey in 2019, the "vast majority of large construction projects go over budget and take 20% longer than expected".
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Law related to construction primarily focuses around contracts and obligations, as well as planning permissions and legal matters on topics such as infrastructure, housing, engineering, insurance, the environment and building warrants.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] A construction project is a complex net of construction contracts and other legal obligations, each of which all parties must carefully consider.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] A contract is the exchange of a set of obligations between two or more parties, and provides structures to manage issues.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] For example, construction delays can be costly, so construction contracts set out clear expectations and clear paths to manage delays.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Poorly drafted contracts can lead to confusion and costly disputes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] At the start of a project, legal advisors seek to identify ambiguities and other potential sources of trouble in the contract structures, and to present options for preventing problems.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] During projects, they work to avoid and resolve conflicts that arise and processes such as negotiation and arbitration may take place.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Design-bid-build is the most common and well-established method of construction procurement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In this arrangement, the architect, engineer or builder acts for the client as the project coordinator.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] They design the works, prepare specifications and design deliverables (models, drawings, etc.), administer the contract, tender the works, and manage the works from inception to completion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In parallel, there are direct contractual links between the client and the main contractor, who, in turn, has direct contractual relationships with subcontractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The arrangement continues until the project is ready for handover.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Design-build became more common from the late 20th century, and involves the client contracting a single entity to provide design and construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In some cases, the design-build package can also include finding the site, arranging funding and applying for all necessary statutory consents.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Typically, the client invites several Design & Build (D&B) contractors to submit proposals to meet the project brief and then selects a preferred supplier.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Often this will be a consortium involving a design firm and a contractor (sometimes more than one of each).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the United States, departments of transportation usually use design-build contracts as a way of progressing projects where states lack the skills or resources, particularly for very large projects.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In a construction management arrangement, the client enters into separate contracts with the designer (architect or engineer), a construction manager, and individual trade contractors.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The client takes on the contractual role, while the construction or project manager provides the active role of managing the separate trade contracts, and ensuring that they complete all work smoothly and effectively together.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the industrialized world, construction usually involves the translation of designs into reality.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Most commonly (i.e.: in a design-bid-build project), the design team is employed by (i.e. in contract with) the property owner.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Depending upon the type of project, a design team may include architects, civil engineers, mechanical engineers, electrical engineers, structural engineers, fire protection engineers, planning consultants, architectural consultants, and archaeological consultants.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] A 'lead designer' will normally be identified to help coordinate different disciplinary inputs to the overall design.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] This may be aided by integration of previously separate disciplines (often undertaken by separate firms) into multi-disciplinary firms with experts from all related fields, or by firms establishing relationships to support design-build processes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] For buildings, building engineering is an emerging discipline that attempts to meet this new challenge.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Traditionally, design has involved the production of sketches, architectural and engineering drawings, and specifications.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some projects may include elements that are designed for off-site construction (see also DfMA, prefabrication and modular building) and are then delivered to the site ready for erection, installation or assembly.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Once contractors and other relevant professionals have been appointed and designs are sufficiently advanced, work may commence on the project site.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some projects require preliminary works, such as land preparation and levelling, demolition of existing structures (see below), or laying foundations, and there are circumstances where this work may be contracted for in advance of finalising the contract and costs for the whole project.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Typically, a construction site will include a secure perimeter to restrict unauthorised access, site access control points, office and welfare accommodation for personnel from the main contractor and other firms involved in the project team, and storage areas for materials, machinery and equipment.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] According to the *McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Architecture and Construction's* definition, construction may be said to have *started* when the first feature of the permanent structure has been put in place, such as pile driving, or the pouring of slabs or footings.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Commissioning is the process of verifying that all subsystems of a new building (or other assets) work as intended to achieve the owner's project requirements and as designed by the project's architects and engineers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] A period after handover (or practical completion) during which the owner may identify any shortcomings in relation to the building specification ('defects'), with a view to the contractor correcting the defect.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Maintenance involves functional checks, servicing, repairing or replacing of necessary devices, equipment, machinery, building infrastructure, and supporting utilities in industrial, business, governmental, and residential installations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Demolition is the discipline of safely and efficiently tearing down buildings and other artificial structures.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Demolition contrasts with deconstruction, which involves taking a building apart while carefully preserving valuable elements for reuse purposes (recycling – see also circular economy).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The output of the global construction industry was worth an estimated $10.8 trillion in 2017, and in 2018 was forecast to rise to $12.9 trillion by 2022, and to around $14.8 trillion in 2030.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] As a sector, construction accounts for more than 10% of global GDP (in developed countries, construction comprises 6–9% of GDP), and employs around 7% of the total employed workforce around the globe (accounting for over 273 million full- and part-time jobs in 2014).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Since 2010, China has been the world's largest single construction market.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The United States is the second largest construction market with a 2018 output of $1.581 trillion.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Construction is a major source of employment in most countries; high reliance on small businesses, and under-representation of women are common traits.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] According to McKinsey research, productivity growth per worker in construction has lagged behind many other industries across different countries including in the United States and in European countries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the United States, construction productivity per worker has declined by half since the 1960s.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some workers may be engaged in manual labour as unskilled or semi-skilled workers; they may be skilled tradespeople; or they may be supervisory or managerial personnel.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Laborers comprise a large grouping in most national construction industries.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the United States, for example, in May 2023, the construction sector employed just over 7.9 million people, of whom 859,000 were laborers, while 3.7 million were construction trades workers (including 603,000 carpenters, 559,000 electricians, 385,000 plumbers, and 321,000 equipment operators).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Large-scale construction requires collaboration across multiple disciplines.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] A project manager normally manages the budget on the job, and a construction manager, design engineer, construction engineer or architect supervises it.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Some models and policy-making organisations promote the engagement of local labour in construction projects as a means of tackling social exclusion and addressing skill shortages.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the UK, the Joseph Rowntree Foundation reported in 2000 on 25 projects which had aimed to offer training and employment opportunities for locally based school leavers and unemployed people.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The Foundation published "a good practice resource book" in this regard at the same time.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Use of local labour and local materials were specified for the construction of the Danish Storebaelt bridge, but there were legal issues which were challenged in court and addressed by the European Court of Justice in 1993.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The court held that a contract condition requiring use of local labour and local materials was incompatible with EU treaty principles.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Later UK guidance noted that social and employment clauses, where used, must be compatible with relevant EU regulation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] There are many routes to the different careers within the construction industry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Unskilled and semi-skilled workers provide general site labor, often have few or no construction qualifications, and may receive basic site training.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Skilled tradespeople have typically served apprenticeships (sometimes in labor unions) or received technical training; this group also includes on-site managers who possess extensive knowledge and experience in their craft or profession.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Skilled manual occupations include carpenters, electricians, plumbers, ironworkers, heavy equipment operators and masons, as well as those involved in project management.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the UK these require further education qualifications, often in vocational subject areas, undertaken either directly after completing compulsory education or through "on the job" apprenticeships.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Professional, technical and managerial personnel often have higher education qualifications, usually graduate degrees, and are trained to design and manage construction processes.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] These roles require more training as they demand greater technical knowledge, and involve more legal responsibility.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Construction is one of the most dangerous occupations in the world, incurring more occupational fatalities than any other sector in both the United States and in the European Union.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In the US in 2019, 1,061, or about 20%, of worker fatalities in private industry occurred in construction.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In 2017, more than a third of US construction fatalities (366 out of 971 total fatalities) were the result of falls; in the UK, half of the average 36 fatalities per annum over a five-year period to 2021 were attributed to falls from height.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Proper safety equipment such as harnesses, hard hats and guardrails and procedures such as securing ladders and inspecting scaffolding can curtail the risk of occupational injuries in the construction industry.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Other major causes of fatalities in the construction industry include electrocution, transportation accidents, and trench cave-ins.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Other safety risks for workers in construction include hearing loss due to high noise exposure, musculoskeletal injury, chemical exposure, and high levels of stress.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Besides that, the high turnover of workers in construction industry imposes a huge challenge of accomplishing the restructuring of work practices in individual workplaces or with individual workers.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Construction has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda (NORA) to identify and provide intervention strategies regarding occupational health and safety issues.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] A study conducted in 2022 found "significant effect of air pollution exposure on construction-related injuries and fatalities", especially with the exposure of nitrogen dioxide.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The construction industry may require transformation at pace and at scale if it is to successfully contribute to achieving the target set out in The Paris Agreement of limiting global temperature rise to 1.5C above industrial levels.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] The World Green Building Council has stated the buildings and infrastructure around the world can reach 40% less embodied carbon emissions but that this can only be achieved through urgent transformation.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Conclusions from industry leaders have suggested that the net zero transformation is likely to be challenging for the construction industry, but it does present an opportunity.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Action is demanded from governments, standards bodies, the construction sector, and the engineering profession to meet the decarbonising targets.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] In 2021, the National Engineering Policy Centre published its report *Decarbonising Construction: Building a new net zero industry,* which outlined key areas to decarbonise the construction sector and the wider built environment.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] Progress is being made internationally to decarbonise the sector including improvements to sustainable procurement practice such as the CO2 performance ladder in the Netherlands and the Danish Partnership for Green Public Procurement.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/construction] There are also now demonstrations of applying the principles of circular economy practices in practice such as Circl, ABN AMRO's sustainable pavilion and the Brighton Waste House.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] A **fire-resistance rating** typically means the duration for which a passive fire protection system can withstand a standard fire resistance test.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] This can be quantified simply as a measure of time, or it may entail other criteria, involving evidence of functionality or fitness for purpose.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] There are many international variations for nearly countless types of products and systems, some with multiple test requirements.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Canada's Institute for Research in Construction (a part of the National Research Council and publisher of Canada's model building code – NBC) requires a special test regime for firestops for plastic pipe penetrants.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Fire endurance tests for this application must be run under 50Pa positive furnace pressure in order to adequately simulate the effect of potential temperature differences between indoor and outdoor temperatures in Canada's winters.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Special hoods are applied here to provide suction on the top side of a test assembly in order to reach the 50Pa pressure differential.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Afterwards, a 30PSI hose-stream test may be applied.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] If critical environmental conditions are not satisfied, an assembly may not be eligible for a fire-resistance rating.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The following classifications may be attained when testing in accordance with UL 72.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] This rating is the requirement in data safes and vault structures for protecting digital information on magnetic media or hard drives.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Temperatures inside the protected chamber must be held below 125 °F (52 °C) for the time period specified, such as Class 125-2 Hour, with temperatures up to 2,000 °F (1,090 °C) outside the vault.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The temperature reading is taken on the inside surfaces of the protective structure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Maintaining the temperature below 125 °F is critical because data is lost above that temperature threshold, even if the media or hard drives appear to be intact.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] This is the rating required to protect microfilm, microfiche, and other film-based information storage media.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Above 150 °F (65.5 °C) film is distorted by the heat and information is lost.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] A Class 150-2 Hour vault must keep the temperature below 150 °F. for at least two hours, with temperatures up to 2,000 °F.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] This rating is the requirement for protecting paper documents.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Above 350 °F (176.7 °C) paper is distorted by the heat and information is lost.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] A Class 350-4 Hour vault must keep the temperature below 350 °F. for at least four hours, with temperatures up to 2,000 °F.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Typically, most countries use the **building elements curve** for residential and commercial spaces, which is nearly identical in most countries as that is what results by burning wood.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The building elements curve is characterized jointly by, including, but not limited to, DIN4102, BS476, ASTM E119, ULC-S101, etc.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] For industrial facilities in the hydrocarbon and petrochemical industries, a hydrocarbon curve (such as UL 1709) is used, reflecting a more rapid temperature rise.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The only commonly used exposure beyond this, apart from the more recent tunnel curves shown above, would be the jet fire exposure standards such as ISO 22899, which are used where equipment may be subject to the extreme heat and momentum effects of jet fire exposure.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] During a fire in a tunnel, as well as in the petrochemical industry, temperatures exceed those of ordinary building (cellulosic) fires.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] This is because the fuel for the fire is hydrocarbons, which burn hotter (compare hydrocarbon curve above to ASTM E119 curve), faster and typically run out of fuel faster as well, compared against timber.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The added complication with tunnels is that heat cannot escape as well as it can in open area.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Instead, the fire is confined to a narrow tube, where pressure and heat build up and spread rapidly, with little room for escape and little chance of compartmentalization.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] Construction of a test sample consists of a mockup of a section of concrete floor, with typical mechanical and electrical utility components (pipes and cables) penetrating the floor assembly.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] A firestop mortar is applied around the penetrations.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The completed test sample is inserted into a furnace such that one side is exposed to a fire.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The test is terminated when the fire stops successfully meet the test criteria in minimizing the amount of heat and smoke allowed to pass through the assembly, when the fire penetrates the fire stops.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] This determines the fire stop **F-Rating**.
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The length of time required for a penetrant or sample on average to exceed a specified average heat rise above ambient at any single location determines the duration for the **FT Rating** (Fire and Temperature).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] If a hose-stream test is passed afterwards, the rating can then be expressed as an **FTH Rating** (Fire, Temperature and Hose-stream).
[src:fire-resistance-rating/fire-resistance-rating] The lowest of the three determines the overall rating.
